name: 2019-09-10 16.11.38 2129695414072050587_tatemodern.jpg
text: Gerhard Richter, Abstract painting, 1990.Richter’s strata-based technique using a scraper, in which the work of construction alternates with destruction..“The picture was painted in successive layers, with long periods of time between each. The first often serves as the background. Even if I don’t use a photograph, it produces an almost illusionistic effect. Firstly, this smooth, melted surface looks like a finished painting that I (…) partially or completely destroy when I start again. The whole thing looks very spontaneous. But (…) what I practice is calculated spontaneity.”.#gerhardrichter #modernart #tatemodern #painting #londonmuseums

name: 2019-09-10 16.20.55 2129700078852604091_tatemodern.jpg
text: Today’s Famous European is Constantin Brâncuși, the exceptional Romanian sculptor. Born in Hobitza (Romania) in 1876, he is considered to be a founding father of modernism and one of the most influential sculptors of the 20th century. Constantin Brâncuși studied art at the National School of Fine Arts in Bucharest from 1898 to 1902 before moving to Paris in 1904. He enrolled in the Ecole des Beaux-Arts and worked as Auguste Rodin’s assistant for three years but parted ways with the famous French sculptor claiming that he did not want to follow the conventional mode of sculpture. Brâncuși established his studio in 1907 and began utilizing abstracted forms, sparking controversy during the 1913 Armory Show in New York. The artist became immersed in the Parisian avant-garde and maintained friendships with Pablo Picasso, Marcel Duchamp, Louise Bourgeois, Henri Matisse, Amedeo Modigliani and others.In 1926, preoccupied by the theme of the bird, he created the sculpture “Bird in Space”, of which he made 15 versions in marble and bronze. Constantin Brancusi sought to convey the essential nature of a bird without the need for traditional representational forms. One year later, the trial “Brancusi vs. the United States” was initiated to determine whether “Bird in Space” was a piece of art or not. Ultimately, the court decided that the sculpture was a work of art. In 1935, the artist was commissioned to create a war memorial in Târgu Jiu, Romania, for which he designed a sculptural ensemble that includes The Table of Silence, The Gate of Kiss, and a monumental Endless Column.The artist died in 1957 in Paris. Brancusi’s works are currently held in the collections of the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York, the Philadelphia Museum of Art, the Centre Georges Pompidou in Paris, and the Tate Modern in London, among others..#brancusi #brâncuși #art #beautiful #sculpture #sculptor #painting #romania #france #paris #orsay #beaubourg #met #nyc #tatemodern #modern #picasso #bucharest #london #summer #picoftheday #artist #travel #traveleurope #famous #history #celebrity #europe #eu #unitedeurope

text: Credevo che la Ricchezza fosse il diverso, il molteplice, il mutevole, e non vedo che pezzi di metallo uniforme che vanno e vengono e si accumulano, e non servono a altro che a moltiplicare se stessi, sempre uguali - Italo Calvino, "Il castello dei destini incrociati"-Yinka Shonibare, "The British Library", an installation of 6,328 hardback books individually covered in colourful ‘Dutch wax print’ fabric and arranged on rows of shelving. Names are printed in gold leaf on the spines of 2,700 of the books, the majority of which are of first- or second-generation immigrants to Britain, both celebrated and lesser-known, who have made significant contributions to British culture and history.#london #modernart #tatemodern

text: Многие люди, идущие в Театр «Глобус» или в Галерею Тейт Модерн, проходят мимо светлого дома с красной дверью: внимание на него обращают немногие, а совершенно напрасно. Табличка на доме гласит: «Сэр Кристофер Рен жил здесь во время строительства Собора Святого Павла». Сэр Кристофер Рен, архитектор, восстановивший центр Лондона после Великого Лондонского пожара 1666-го года.Помимо всемирно известного Собора Святого Павла, к числу сооружений Кристофера Рена принадлежат Кенсингтонский дворец, Хэмптон-корт, Военный госпиталь в Челси и многие другие здания, без которых невозможно представить Лондон.P.S. И ещё, табличка сообщает, что «в 1502-м году в этом доме останавливалась Екатерина Арагонская, первая жена Генриха VIII, во время своего первого визита в Лондон» 👸🏻#cardinalswharf #bankside #banksidelondon #christopherwren #london #england #england🇬🇧 #greatbritain #unitedkingdom #unitedkingdom🇬🇧 #tatemodern #лондон #англия #англия🇬🇧 #великобритания #великобритания🇬🇧 #кристоферрен #тейтмодерн

name: 2019-09-10 19.05.11 2129782756494825943_tatemodern.jpg
text: "Quand, en 1945, Hiroshima fut détruite par une bombe atomique, il a été rapporté que la première créature vivante à émerger dans le paysage désolé était un champignon matsutake.Comprendre l'atome a été le point culminant des rêves humains obsédés par la maîtrise de la nature. Mais ce fut tout aussi bien le début de la fin de ce type de rêves. La bombe d'Hiroshima a tout changé. D'un seul coup, on a pris conscience que les humains pouvaienf détruire toute possibilité de vie, de viabilité, sur la planète, que ce soit de manière intentionnelle ou non. Cette prise de conscience n'a fait qu'augmenter quand nous avons appris ce qu'étaient la pollution, l'extinction des espèces et le changement climatique. Une moitié de la précarité actuelle est le lot de la Terre : quelles sortes de perturbations humaines pouvons-nous supporter? En dépit de tous les discours sur le développement durable, quelles sont nos chances de transmettre à nos descendants, de toutes les espèces, un environnement vivable?" -le champignon de la fin du monde, Anna Lowenhaupt Tsing Photo prise par @yannickoddo : (2019) Olafur Eliasson, Tate Modern, London#london #tatemodern #tate #art #olafureliasson #light #annatsing #lechampignondelafindumonde #ecologie #earth #nature #life

name: 2019-09-10 19.43.44 2129802160510504096_tatemodern.jpg
text: The Natalia Goncharova exhibition at the @tate modern exceeded all expectations. I’m going to have to dedicate some time to blog about it as she really was an extraordinary person, especially when you think of the society at the start of the 20th Century. She did things like paint her face and walk down the streets which drew criticism and several of her paintings were pulled as indecent by the State..I love how she chose to adapt her artistic style to whatever influenced her. Here I’ve shown three separate paintings of the same subject, peasant women. Notice how her style goes from realist to cubist. I love that she didn’t confine herself to any artistic boundaries. #nataliagoncharova #tatemodern #art #russianart #womenartists

name: 2019-09-10 20.49.59 2129835506979578849_tatemodern.jpg
text: Aria dura per la finzione di uno scorcio urbano Panama - omaggio a Yves Klein: ho ricreato il suo tipico e vivido blu (IKB - International Klein Blue) miscelando il pigmento oltremare al colore che utilizzo maggiormente: l’acrilico. Come Klein ho dipinto una tela monocroma dove il blu diviene la rappresentazione dello spazio eliminando ogni individualità e riferimento all'umano. Sulla lastra ho raffigurato un paesaggio di Panama utilizzando altri 2 dei principali colori della pittorica di Klein, il rosa e l'oro. Nella sua poetica il blu è associato al Nirvana, alla pace e allo svuotamento, il rosa al corpo, al sangue, alla ridiscesa sulla terra e all'incarnazione, mentre l'oro è metafora della materia illuminata dalla vita, inteso come intermediario tra mondo visibile ed invisibile. Perciò ho utilizzato questi colori per simboleggiare le parti costituenti del paesaggio urbano: sullo sfondo la “natura” infinita in blu, su cui l’uomo ha poi costruito le sue strutture urbane, il suo corpo sociale attraverso la materia e i materiali.#pietrodente #ariadura #klein #punto #linea #grattacielo #artecontemporanea #contemporaryart #blue #panama #newproject #tatemodern #particolare

name: 2019-09-10 22.03.58 2129872737450558360_tatemodern.jpg
text: LONDON WEEKEND HIGHLIGHT REEL:🇬🇧 Tate Modern. Free modern art museum which was super rad. It’s multi level, and you can go all the way up the roof where you can get a great view of London. .🇬🇧 Burrow Market. Top fave places for sure!! You can get free samples of cheeses, meats, honey, and then grab a quick bite at a street food vendor. We got Indian since that’s known to be amazing in London. We had a lentil pancake stuffed with potatoes + chickpeas drizzled with yogurt sauce and topped with pomegranate seeds. .🇬🇧 Ferry to Greenwich and stroll around Greenwich. The express ferry leaves from the South Bank (close to Burrow Market) for only 10£. It’s a quick 20 minute ride with cool views (sit outside). Then, you can wander around the town and head to Greenwich Observatory where you can get an incredible panoramic view of London. You can also take a cheesy picture at the Prime Meridian where the latitude changes. .🇬🇧 Flat White + Brekky at Chairs & Coffee. I loved the vibe of this coffee shop, and they also have a full menu of specialty scrambled eggs, avo toast and other brunch treats. . 🇬🇧 Hyde Park.  We got to wander Hyde Park where we sat outside Lido and drank lattes along the Serpentine. It was a gorgeous day, and then we walked towards the Italian Gardens and sat in the sunshine talking about corporate burnout, walking therapy, and breakups. It’s a great place for a picnic, reading, or running! NEGATIVE THOUGHTS OBSERVED:❌ I spent way too much money going out in Camden and it wasn’t worth it. I should’ve stayed in. ❌ Everyone is dressed so cute here, and I look terrible. ❌ I will never find a job that I like. This is hopeless. What am I even trying to do with my life? [this was a very nasty thought train after a night out drinking while trying to fall asleep] ❌ I have such a shitty attitude sometimes. I wish I was just happy all the time. Why am I so difficult? .As with anything, things rise and fall! My thoughts have been very intriguing to observe! I had an epiphany that it doesn’t matter where I go or what I do- I’m on this trip by myself and I’m the creator of this experience. Good things take patience and work ✨

text: SHAHRIAR AHMAD Born 1979, Kermanshah/Iran..SHAHRIAR AHMADI started self-training calligraphy by himself before he starts the Art School. During his professional career, Shahriar Ahmadi has tried to maintain the relation between the image and the text in his work in accordance with the Iranian painting tradition.This relationship, through the influence of the abstract expressionist movement, has created a new form of art, which, while purely formalistic, also expresses poetic concepts. For this reason, Shahriar Ahmadi’s painting curtains can be seen as a confrontation between narration and abstraction...#artist #art #abstractexpressionism #contemporaryart #art #iranianartist #irancontemporary #artist #artgallery #artwork #painting #contemporaryart #exhibition #marbella #resort #costadelsol #spain #iran #museum #farhangfoundation #tatemodern #valentino #sothebys #christies #biennale#russia #france #switzerland #italy #london #paris

text: SHAHRIAR AHMAD Born 1979, Kermanshah/Iran..In 1995, he won the First Environment Award in Japan and in 2007 he won the international PaintingBiennial of the Islamic world. He had more than fifteen individual exhibition in Tehran, Zurich, Lucerne, Dubai, Istanbul, London and more than 150 group exhibitions in Iran, switzerland, France, United Kingdom, Germany, Italy, USA, Turkey, UAE, Japan, Venezuela, Lebanon, Kuwait, China and others.His works kept in prestigious private and government collections and the museums.He was invited to Lucerne, Switzerland in 2010 by the Art Bond Foundation.He attended to Bienniale in 2015.In 2016, VALENTINO the fashion brand had hanged 2 of his artworks on his winter collection runway.Shahriar Ahmadi paintings are bought and sold in world famous auction houses like Christie’s, Sotheby’s and Bonhams...#artist #art #abstractexpressionism #contemporaryart #art #iranianartist #irancontemporary #artist #artgallery #artwork #painting #contemporaryart #exhibition #marbella #resort #costadelsol #spain #iran #museum #farhangfoundation #tatemodern #valentino #sothebys #christies #biennale#russia #france #switzerland #italy #london #paris

name: 2019-09-10 22.28.19 2129884989524515833_tatemodern.jpg
text: Галерея Tate Modern находится в бывшем здании электростанции  Bankside Power Station.  Спроектировал ее тот же человек, что  и придумал красные телефонные будки. Он же построил другую известную электростанцию -  Battersea. Помните  обложку "Animals"  Pink Floyd  с трубами, так вот это  Battersea. У Бэнксайда трубы тоже были, на 12 метров ниже Собора Святого Павла, который  напротив нее. Работала Бэнксайд в свое время на нефти и была закрыта в 1981-м.  Выпив на террасе сидра (в принципе, в Tate Modern можно ходить  просто ради вида), присмотрела себе заставку для смартфона. Художница Evelyn Axell. Бельгийский поп-арт. Шестидесятые. Космонавтика и Валентина Терешкова. Змейка и скафандр на картине настоящие.  А что у вас на заставке  телефона?

name: 2019-09-11 02.44.21 2130013860187273548_tatemodern.jpg
text: 🌈OLAFUR ELIASSON🌈 We’re baaack! We visited ‘In Real Life’ again today and it was so interesting to see it all for a second time. I think the fog was more dense and sweeter-tasting this time, which was awesome, but I was so disappointed to see that the moss wall, ‘Beauty’ (the rain room) and the kaleidoscope windows have all been roped off to prevent anyone touching them. I absolutely understand the need to protect the artwork and I guess people might have been slipping over in the rain room, but it was such a shame to lose the multi-sensory elements of some of the pieces. That being said, we did have a lovely time and it’s still my favourite exhibition of the year so far! #londonbaby #londontoddler #dayout #tatemodern #kidsingalleries #inreallife #artforkids #artforall #learningathome #eyfs #londonlife #familytime Sorry, had to delete and repost- half of my pictures were white!?!

text: ‘PRAGMA’ Gold (TREE OF LOVE Rug series) based on real ‘Tree of Life’ Persian rugs, REY UK 2019Follow Amazing Artist @reyzorro Pragma love in the BiblePragma is a kind of practical love founded on reason or duty and one's longer-term interests. Sexual attraction takes a back seat in favour of personal qualities and compatibilities shared goals and making it work. In the days of arranged marriages, pragma must have been very common.Tree of life rugs, also known as Tree rugs earn distinction as a representation of one of the most timeless religious symbols of human life, its use preceding Christianity and Islam. Ancient cultures throughout Europe and Asia view the tree of life as a link between man and heaven. Often, in Oriental rug producing areas, Tree of Life rugs are produced as prayer rugs. In Islam, the Tree of Life remains an important metaphor for the pathway between Heaven, Earth, and the underworld of Hell. #contemporaryart#reyzorro#whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #damienhirst #NewMediaArt#artbasel

name: 2019-09-11 04.24.41 2130064360714661573_tatemodern.jpg
text: ‘Feelings are facts!’ - colorful first position in front of one of the beautifully thought provoking works of Olafur Eliasson. Today was a good day. I made art, moving my body in a contemporary ballet class that as usual let my deepest emotions free; I  saw art at the National Portrait Gallery in the world of Cindy Sherman; I breathe art at Tate modern, walking through Eliasson magical explorations of space, light, nature; and I settle into art in a slow but powerful yoga class that brought everything together. I didn’t plan today. It simply happened because of what my feelings were telling me at the moment. A little bit like my life right now, I’m silencing the rational side, to let the heart speak. As Yvonne Rayner said ‘Feelings are facts’ and ‘In real Life’ this is all that matters #domoreart ..#dancer #firstposition #yogi #yogainspiration #yogaeverywhere #yogaeverydamnday #london #dancing #ballerina #feelmore #yogalife #art #iglondon #contemporaryart #livelondon #livemore #adventure #tatemodern #light #londoner #olafureliasson #discoverlondon #arthistorian #feelingsarefacts #wanderlust #foodforyourthoughts #arthistorian #neverstopexploring

name: 2019-09-11 16.55.53 2130442454620780315_tatemodern.jpg
text: The Beguiling of Merlin is a painting by the British Pre-Raphaelite painter Edward Burne-Jones that was created between 1872 and 1877.The painting depicts a scene from the Arthurian legend about the infatuation of Merlin with the Lady of the Lake, Nimue. Merlin is flattered by the aggressive attention of Vivien – an interloper into King Arthur’s Court – and eventually, he tells her the secret of a spell that leaves its victim ‘Closed in the four walls of a hollow tower / From which was no escape for evermore.’ As soon as she hears the secret, Vivien works the magic on Merlin. In this painting, Merlin is shown trapped, helpless in a hawthorn bush as Nimue reads from a book of spells.The painting shows Merlin and Vivien at the moment of betrayal. Merlin exchanges a look with Vivien, who holds open a book of spells. Vivien’s diaphanous robes accentuate the contours of her body; her profile is expressionless. Merlin is exhausted, wilting into the tree’s cavity, and the look he gives Vivien is ambiguous: perhaps resentful, or grudgingly respectful?To book our Walk Through British Art, please visit our website https://www.nejasartwalks.com/british-art-at-tate-britainor email us info@nejasartwalks.com#preRaphaelites #JohnEverettMillais #millais #victorianengland #victorianart #victorianmasculinity #art #londonart #Londonartgallery #artmuseum #artdaily  #painting #londonartwalks #nejasartwalks #britishart #EdwardBurneJones #londra #londres #tatebritain #tatemodern #visitlondon #merlin #kingarthur

name: 2019-09-11 17.08.32 2130448821984618818_tatemodern.jpg
text: David Batchelor, Spectrum of Brick Land 2, 2017..Batchelor is fascinated by the intense artificial colours that surround us in modern cities. Most of the colour we now see is plastic or metallic. One side of the sculpture represents vivid illuminated colours. The other is « like the back of an old stereo ». He relates this ‘front-and-back relashionship’ to the city environment, distinct from the ‘in the round’ experience of the natural world..#davidbatchelor #tatemodern #weekendinlondon #contemporaryart #sculptures #neon

text: Really great selection in the Artists Rooms Ed Ruscha show at Tate Modern.For me Ruscha’s works on paper are his best. This set of etchings from 2001 that layer and intersect streets in LA and San Francisco caught my eye, partly because it’s different to anything by Ruscha I’d seen before. Title of the portfolio is Los Francisco San Angeles.A Ruscha work on paper or two is definitely part of my fantasy collection (would also include a copy of Twenty Six Gasoline Stations, and wouldn’t say no to a copy of Nine Swimming Pools either)Apologies as ever for selfie reflections.#edruscha #artistsrooms #tatemodern #fantasyartcollection #LosFranciscoSanAngeles #gosee

text: 올라퍼 엘리아슨 런던 테이트모던 회고전 Olafur Eliasson: In Real Life exhibition at Tate Modern in London.특히 좋았던 것은 한 치 앞도 안 보이는 빛과 안개의 길 <Your Blind Passenger>(2010) (photo 1,2,3), 처음 보면 추상적인 미디어아트인가 싶은데 알고 보면 진주의 광택을 새롭게 보여주는 것인 <A Description of A Reflection>(1995)(photo 4), 과학과 시의 결합 <Stardust Particle>(2014)(photo5,6)그밖에 간판 작품 <Your Uncertain Shadow>(2010)(photo 7), 신작 <In Real Life>(2019)(photo8), <Your Spiral View>(2002)(photo 9).그리고 사진을 제대로 찍을 수 없어 안 올리지만, 4년 전 파리 퐁다시옹 루이뷔통에서 보고 정말 감탄한 적이 있는 <Big Bang Fountain>(2014)을 여기에서 다시 보고 또 정말 감탄했다. 이건 내 사진 실력으로는 도저히 표현할 수 없고 말로 설명하면, 반복적으로 튀어 오르는 물을 스트로보스코프(어둠 속에서 조명을 껐다 켰다 반복하는 장치)로 비추어, 순간 순간 다른 모습의 물덩어리를 보게 하는 것인데, 마치 공중에 뜬 채 시시각각 변하는 투명하게 빛나는 유동체 조각을 보는 것 같은 느낌이다. 정말 아름답다..이렇게 올라퍼 엘리아슨은 빛과 물과 같은 가장 단순한 자연 요소를 미술관 안으로 들여와, 놀랍도록 단순한 몇 가지 장치로, 하지만 그만큼 놀랍도록 창조적인 아이디어로, 자연을 다른 맥락에 놓고 사람들이 그걸 완전히 새로운 관점에서 지각하게끔 한다. 그리고 그러한 예술의 힘을 사회적 변화 (특히 그가 관심 있는 기후 변화 문제 해결)를 위해 사용하곤 한다..몇 년 전 리움 삼성미술관에서 나와 인터뷰했을 때 그는 이렇게 말했다. “자연이 내게 영감을 주는 이유는 무척 민주적이기 때문입니다. 어떤 사람이든 자연에 대해서는 한 마디씩 하지요. 내 진정한 관심사는 (인간의 지각) 경험의 구성입니다. 빛과 자연은 경험을 살펴보고, 연구하고, 유발하는 좋은 재료입니다. 나는 자연에 대해 말하곤 하지만, 사실, 내 진짜 관심사는 사람입니다. 자연은 사람들의 마음을 움직이고 그들에게 닿기 위한 길일 뿐입니다.”.Artist Olafur Eliasson repeatedly said that his art in general encompasses a certain perception of nature and brings the natural world from outside to inside museums. He added that he puts nature in a different context so that people can see it from a whole new angle and that he uses the power of art to affect social change..When I asked him during an interview a few years ago at Leeum, Samsung Museum of Art, in Seoul, why nature, particularly light, is a constant source of inspiration to the artist, he said, “It is because it’s very democratic. Everybody has opinion about that. My real interest is in the structure of experience. Light and nature are good materials to examine, investigate and provoke experiences. I often talk about nature but, in truth, my real interest is people. Nature is just a way of touching and reaching people.”.#olafureliasson #올라퍼엘리아슨 #테이트모던 #tatemodern #contemporaryart #현대미술 #동시대미술 #런던미술관 #전시회 #전시회추천

name: 2019-09-11 22.53.40 2130622534588907459_tatemodern.jpg
text: What an honour and a privilege to be one of the names included on the spine of a book/ database ( this time I sit next to @zahahadidarchitects and a row above from @chalayanstudio two Middle Eastern heroes) in phenomenal artist Yinka Shonibare @shonibarestudio ‘The British Library ‘. An incredibly timely installation at Tate Modern that highlights the impact of immigration on British culture and invites visitors to join in the discussionPrinted in gold on the spines of 2,700 of the books are the names of first or second-generation immigrants to Britain. Whether celebrated or lesser known, they have all made significant contributions to British culture and history. There are also books with the names of those who have opposed immigration. Other books are unmarked, suggesting that the story of immigration in Britain is still being written.At a time where immigrants are being ‘othered’ and treated like insects in probably one of the worst times in my memory for experiencing and witnessing hostility and isolation as an immigrant. This installation is beautiful, engaging and powerful and I encourage all to visit it. Congratulations and thank you Yinka and @kerryngreenberg and the Tate for recognising us and the need for this incredible workYinka Shonibare CBE was born, studied and lives in London, but grew up in Lagos, Nigeria. He was awarded the CBE (Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire) in 2019 and has added the title to his professional name. His dual identity as British-Nigerian has been the starting point for much of his work.  #yinkashonibare #tatemodern #england #london #migrants #immigration #refugeeartists #migrantartists #iranianfemaleartists #iranianartist #britishartists #womeninthearts #womeninphotography #refugeewomen Thanks @culturemanny for the portrait of me! ❤️

text: Viennese design duo Mischer'Traxler created a mobile-like light installation for the Austrian contribution to London's first design biennale in 2016. Named LeveL in response to the Biennale theme Utopia by Design.The sculptures pendent-shaped lights are attached to a network of branches that unbalance when visitors brush past and causing the light to dim. The lights reached maximum luminosity when each of the branches were in perfect equilibrium, and their dimmest when the branches were unsettled. The piece follows on from the pair's earlier Equilumen lamp design. #somersethouse #designbiennale2016 #design #lighting #sculpture #levelup #london #tate #tatemodern #tatemodernmuseum  ##tatemodernlondon #london #londonist #london_city_photo #londonbylondoners #london🇬🇧 #londonlifeinc #londonphotography #londoncitylife #londonart #londonforyou #londonartscene #explorelondon #exploringlondon #instagay #gayphotographer #gaystagram #londondesign #vienesedesign #mischertraxlerk

text: Repost from Tate Modern @tate _____________________________________________________ Who's seen Sarah Sze's 'Seamless' at Tate Modern?The title of Sze's sculpture refers to the way it sweeps across the room in a way that appears seamless. Expanding into doorways, corners and even the space behind the walls, it draws attention to the architecture of the gallery. Sze describes the sculpture as a 'tool for understanding space and time' as all the tools she used to make the work have become part of the work itself.Explore the sculptural installation on level four of Tate Modern — free!  #tatemodern #exhibition #modernart #contemporaryart #art

name: 2019-09-12 00.28.35 2130670301428702535_tatemodern.jpg
text: We are closely related to nature, even if we think another way. The Danish-Icelandic artist Olafur Eliasson has always paid attention to it. His new exhibition "In Real Life" in Tate Modern contains his most remarkable works that are devoted to such topics as migration, climate-changing, the early space researches, natural phenomena. During the exhibition, not only recent masterpieces (for example, "Stardust particle", 2014) are shown. Eliasson's "Beauty", 1993, "Moss Wall",1994 are there too.  ___________________________________________ Together with @ecc_venice, we are working hard on creating an unforgettable exhibition ”Public Architecture - Future for Europe” which will be held in Moscow Architecture Museum. Don't miss it - on January 30, 2020 😇👌🏻 #design #art #architecture #contemporaryart #contemporaryarchitecture #contemporaryfineart #arts #artwork #tatemodern #eccrussia #eccitaly

text: Gallery Exhibition Opening tonight: White Cube Gallery, 18.00-20.00 pm.⠀White Cube Gallery will present an exhibition of works by Dora Maurer tonight. The paintings above are from her current exhibition at Tate Modern.⠀White Cube gallery will focus on the paintings from  these series as well as the others ( “Overlapping Series”).⠀“The subject of Maurer’s art is the way colour behaves, it’s vibrations and imaginary movements”, - the art historian  David  Feher has said. Her art is inventive and playful, the themes she explores are the themes of movement, displacement, perception and transformation.⠀The exhibition will also include the works of Mona Hatoum  and Harmony Hammond.

name: 2019-09-12 01.36.06 2130704294592535402_tatemodern.jpg
text: I was lucky enough to visit the Dorothea Tanning exhibition— the first ever to span her seven(!)-decade career— at the @tate Modern museum in London this summer, and I fell in love with her. @blipswitch’s new movement installation, “Fever”— informed by Tanning’s surrealist works— explores the parallel and divergent realities of our dreams and the power of a time and space not yet tangible, but lives in infinite possibility. So I find it fitting that the only photo I happened to snap of her work is entitled “Insomnies”.P.S. Go check out dorotheatanning.org.THIS Friday 9/13 - Saturday 9/148:00PM“Fever” at @revolveatx*Tickets via link in bio*.“Insomnies” (1957, oil on canvas)In her own words, on this painting: “...It would also be not quite there, immediately. I wanted to lead the eye into spaces that hid, revealed, transformed all at once and where there would be some never-before-seen image, as if it had appeared with no help from me...”

name: 2019-09-12 02.16.11 2130724465469124906_tatemodern.jpg
text: I was looking at some old pictures the other day...and found this interior shot of the 2nd floor concourse of the Blavatnik Building (then known as the Switch House) nine days before the public opening. It was this really weird mix of excitement and fear that we wouldn't be ready on time. It all smelt of sawdust with all the unsealed oak floors giving out their smell.Three years on the same floors have the patina of daily use smeared with the dust of the city and its inhabitants. A true moment of genius by H&dM in the original building to let the city dirty up the museum, show it for the communal space that it ought to want to be.A metaphor for the modern city, in a modern art museum. #empty #architecture #architecturelovers #archilovers  #LondonArchitecture #archidaily #architexture #HerzogandDeMeuron #modernism #TateModern #roughsownoak #chasinglight #installationart #london_only #LondonbyLondoners #lightandshadow #architecturephotography #LondonCalling #minimalism #myLondon #artoftheday #artoninstagram #teamPixel

name: 2019-09-12 02.16.25 2130724579446321912_tatemodern.jpg
text: Have been busy over the last few months preparing for the @hyphenlabs @tateexchange takeover. #higherresolution #higherpower.Visit us at Tate Modern in the pursuit of Higher Resolution in our ever evolving digital realms.September 17th - 29th (link in bio)!!!....Join international collective Hyphen-Labs and question our relationships with digital platforms, the power behind technology, and how art can be used as a tool of intervention as they launch the fourth year of Tate Exchange, responding to the theme of 'Power'.Collaborating with Tate Exchange Associates and global guest contributors, including Romy Gad el Rab and Caroline Sinders, examine what we share with machines and the algorithms that define our privacy, behaviour and digital rights, inspired by the question ‘how did we get here?’ Focusing on technology and the next generation of ‘higher power’, explore the creation of power and the tools to disrupt, resist and redistribute it through an immersive sequence of interventions and conversations, talks and workshops across multiple spaces....🎮🌐🔌📲.#exhibition #tatemodern #TateExchange #technology #ai #data #surveillance #performance #debate #thegreathack #collaboration #power

text: Ach London, was ist nur los mit uns Zweien? Irgendwie ist die Luft ein bisschen raus. Wie konnte das nur passieren? Wir haben uns doch so lange so gut verstanden? Liegt es daran, dass ich mittlerweile selbst mitten in der Stadt wohne und es dort immer zu laut und zu wenig grün ist? Oder daran, dass ich nicht mehr so gerne konsumiere und doch nicht Hipster genug bin? Ich weiß es nicht ...Wir hatten trotzdem einen schönen Tag mit Fish & Chips auf dem Borough Market, mit Artsy-Fartsy-Fotos in der Tate Modern, mit Shakespeare, mit Ben Wilsons Kaugummikunst auf der Millenium Bridge, mit High Tea und dem obligatorischen Buckingham-Palace-Selfie. Jetzt ist aber auch gut. Darf ich endlich mit Polly losfahren gen Süd-Westen?? text: ‘PRAGMA’ multi (TREE OF LOVE Rug series) based on real ‘Tree of Life’ Persian rugs, REY UK 2019Pragma love in the BiblePragma is a kind of practical love founded on reason or duty and one's longer-term interests. Sexual attraction takes a back seat in favour of personal qualities and compatibilities shared goals and making it work. In the days of arranged marriages, pragma must have been very common.Tree of life rugs, also known as Tree rugs earn distinction as a representation of one of the most timeless religious symbols of human life, its use preceding Christianity and Islam. Ancient cultures throughout Europe and Asia view the tree of life as a link between man and heaven. Often, in Oriental rug producing areas, Tree of Life rugs are produced as prayer rugs. In Islam, the Tree of Life remains an important metaphor for the pathway between Heaven, Earth, and the underworld of Hell And it is about sound and the sound of the words we all borrow. #contemporaryart#reyzorro#whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #NewMediaArt#artbasel

name: 2019-09-12 11.48.44 2131012633440909160_tatemodern.jpg
text: 🇧🇪MARCEL BROODTHAERS 🇧🇪▪️Moules Casserole | 1964 | @hauserwirth▪️"Don't feel sold before you have been bought.” —Marcel Broodthaers▪️The Belgian artist Marcel Broodthaers was one of the leading conceptual artists in post-war Europe. Much of his work from the early 1960s engaged with the theme of national identity, especially in the wake of World War II. Broodthaers famously kept his art witty and playful despite the seriousness of his subject matter.▪️Mussels, considered the national dish of Belgium, became a popular motif for Broodthaers as he explored his Belgian identity. Filled with countless individual shells, the brimming pot may be a metaphor for Belgium’s diversity. On the other hand, the fact that the shells are empty might be a commentary on the uncertainty surrounding post-war Belgium. This interpretive freedom is a hallmark of conceptual art that gives the viewer power to decide a work’s meaning.▪️The title of this work is also a clever play on words. In French, “la moule” (a mussel) sounds the same as “le moule” (a mold). The latter version has a few meanings in itself. Firstly, and most obviously, it could reference the artistic tool used by sculptors. But the word can also be read in a social context. For example, in a 1961 poem about Mussels, Broodthaers wrote, “This clever thing has avoided society’s mold / She’s cast herself in her very own.”▪️I love that this work incorporates all three meanings of the word “moule.” The pot exists both as a literal artistic mold and a metaphorical social mold — unable to contain the mussels, a symbol of post-war Belgium. Thinking about the work this context, I can’t help but wonder if it’s actually a self portrait of the eccentric Broodthaers, who spent his life upending the conventions of “society’s mold.”

name: 2019-09-12 14.36.19 2131096982050193033_tatemodern.jpg
text: The Birthday (c.1915).🎨 Painted by Marc Chagall.Born: 6 July 1887, Liozna, Russian Empire.Died: 28 March 1985, Saint-Paul-de-Vence, France. (aged 97).🖼  Oil on cardboard 81 x 99,7 cm..📝 How Marc Chagall painted his own birthday - inspired by the love and gifts of his muse Bella.."The Birthday” or “Anniversary” as it’s also known, is a 1915 Marc Chagall composition featuring a simple interior typical of Russian provincial tastes of the turn of the 20th century.The woman in the painting is none other than Chagalls’ beloved first wife Bella Rosenfeld whom the artist met in St. Petersburg in 1908.Bella, in a simple black dress is shown tilted forward towards the window as if running, holding a festive bouquet of flowers. Chagall – floating lovingly above her, kissing her with his head bent and twisted, his torso turned away from her. This is an intimate setting, meant for the loved one, and that’s how the viewer gets a feeling of being in the same room as the couple and almost intruding upon an intimate moment. Like so many of Marc Chagall’s other loving tributes to his wife, this painting is filled with intimacy, caring affection, love and warmth.Bella’s own memoirs, written thirty-five years after their first meeting, she recalls how she had managed, with great difficulty, to discover Marc’s date of birth, and visited him on that day, carrying food and flowers in embroidered shawls and Chagall began to paint.In his autobiography “My Life,” Chagall described his first encounter with Bella: “Her silence is mine, her eyes mine. It is as if she knows everything about my childhood, my present, my future, as if she can see right through me.” The color palette is interesting for a different reason. The primary colors in this painting are red, black, white and green – the principal colors used by Kazemir Malevich, the Suprematists and abstractionists of VHUTEMAS. It was the preferred palette for the new century, the new language of Russian modernism.The painting is in the permanent collection of the Museum of Modern Art in New York..(Fig 2, 3, 4 : Details)(Fig 5 : Bella and Marc Chagall in Paris, 1938)...🎂.

name: 2019-09-12 16.11.10 2131144719229605859_tatemodern.jpg
text: OLAFUR ELIASSON : In Real Life. This exhibition brings together over 40 works made between 1990 and today. Eliasson’s art comes from his concern with nature, honed through his time spent in Iceland, his research into geometry and his ongoing investigations into how we perceive, feel about and shape the world around us. He puts experience at the center of his art. He hopes that as you encounter it you become more aware of your senses. You add meaning to the works as you bring your associations and memories to these experiences. You might also become aware of the people around you with whom you form temporary community. This heightened awareness of yourself and the other people creates a new sense of responsibility. Ultimately, he believes that art can have a strong impact on the world outside the museum. Photos taken by @pipsbrabyn #olafureliasson #inreallife #tatemodern #londonart #contenporaryart #modernart #danishicelandicartist #geometric #weatherart #climatechange

name: 2019-09-12 16.24.53 2131151628950384694_tatemodern.jpg
text: In 1849, John Everett Millais's painting Christ in the House of His Parents was seen as sacrilegious on account of its extreme verisimilitude and quirkiness. The conventional saccharine quality of Victorian religious art was absent. ————————————————————————Millais's Christ child, shown with a symbolic bleeding palm, was described by Charles Dickens as "a hideous, wry-necked, blubbering, red-haired boy in a nightgown" who appeared to have received a poke playing in an adjacent gutter, while his kneeling mother "would stand out from the rest of the company as a monster in the vilest cabaret in France or in the lowest gin-shop in England". ————————————————————————To book our Walk Through British Art, please visit our website https://www.nejasartwalks.com/british-art-at-tate-britainor email us info@nejasartwalks.com#preRaphaelites #JohnEverettMillais #millais #victorianengland #victorianart #victorianmasculinity #art #londonart #Londonartgallery #artmuseum #artdaily  #painting #londonartwalks #nejasartwalks #britishart #artinspiration #londra #londres #tatebritain #tatemodern #visitlondon #WilliamHolmanHunt #CharlesDickens

text: 테이트 모던의 <Olafur Eliasson: IN REAL LIFE >전시에 다녀왔어요. 우리 팀원 모두가 너무너무 좋아하는 작가라 들어가기도 전에 벌써 좋아서 괜히 오랫동안 설렘을 즐겼어요 (초코머핀 먹으면서).올라퍼 엘리아슨은 자연과 현상, 날씨, 감각 등을 연구하고 모든 장르를 다뤄요. 이끼, 얼음, 물, 안개, 빛과 반짝이는 금속까지! 모두 흥미로운 재료가 되지요..우리 몸을 통해 변화하는 작품 속에서 우리의 감각을 더 많이 일깨운답니다..자연과 현상에 대한 이야기는 너무 일상적일수도, 반대로 너무 어려울 수도 있지만 이 작품들 속에서는 그냥 느끼기만 하면 그걸로 충분했어요..게다가 이 느낌들을 아이들도 더 이해해볼 수 있도록 미술관에서 제공하는 가족용 팜플렛이 인상깊었어요. 작품별로 흥미로운 질문과 제안들이 있었답니다..아이들과 이야기하기 위한 적절한 질문의 중요성을 다시 한 번 깨닫게 되었지요. 그리고 테이트 모던에 가신다면 natalie bell 빌딩 3층 카페에서 꼭 초코 머핀을 드셔야 합니다!🌿🌿.#tatemodern #london #olafurelliasson #artwork #exhibition #에이드런 #해외탐방 #미술관 #대화 #어린이 #senses #초코머핀 #짱

name: 2019-09-12 21.48.49 2131312259662411549_tatemodern.jpg
text: How does the shape of light look like? I guess if every person of this world took just a minute to answer to this question, we would have a very luminous perspective..But we already have some answers as every designer creating lamps and light fixtures gives one. And contemporary design is full of surprising shapes that, beyond aesthetics and poetry must be correlated with sustainability, new technologies and pure experiment..When visiting the amazing @rossana_orlandi gallery in Milan, this spring, I was very pleased to see one of those beautifully crafted light fixtures. I had already written about the “Filamento” project, of Spanish duo @mayicestudio. And it was a pleasure to see with my own eyes the sculptural silhouette made out of a single piece of glass more than one meter long that, when illuminated, becomes an incandescent object beyond shape or physical elements..In the same Milano gallery I discovered the “Mila” lamps world of Canadian designer @matthew.mccormick, a pearl-like shaped glass balls challenged to maintain equilibrium in a metallic frame. A design game of volumes and minimalism inspired, it seems, by the shape of the artist’s wife pregnant belly. For me, the lamps can also be giant precious earrings embellishing any celling..Another contemporary designer I admire is Spanish Nacho Carbonell, a real artist, whose lamps and chandeliers are ethereal beings living at the border of functionality and art. His collections, “Cocoon” and “Light Mesh” combine sand, textile and metal creating fragile and yet very powerful sculptures..Now it should be easier for us, the rest of mortals, to describe or represent the shape of light... And by the way, in 2018 at @tate was exhibited an interesting dialogue between photography and abstract art called “Shape of Light”..📷 @mayicestudio @matthew.mccormick @galleriagiorgiofranchetti @no6mag.#no6mag #shapes #design #lamps #theshapeoflight #nachocarbonell #mayicestudio #filamento #matthewmccormick #mila #lights #cocoon #tatemodern #sculpture #art #rossanaorlandi

text: This particular room at the Tate Modern was in the Olafur Eliasson exhibition. ⁣⁣It’s absolutely full of dry ice smoke and at times it’s so thick you can barely see past the end of your nose. I’m not normally claustrophobic, but I found this rather uncomfortable to be it. ⁣⁣This exhibition runs until the beginning of January and I would highly recommend taking kids along to it (although maybe give this room a miss if your little ones don’t like enclosed spaces). ⁣⁣#tatemodern #olafureliasson #artmuseum #modernart #dayoutinlondon #latenightopening #thingstodoinlondon #bigkid #dryice #claustrophobic #dayoutwithkids #nanny

text: Taking it back this Thursday to a couple of weeks ago when I visited 1 of my favorite art spaces the @Tate Modern in London💙. I moved slowly as I stood before works of art, made by familiar + unfamiliar artists to me, —that moved me to complete stillness. Works that reminded me of the possibilities material, sparked my curiosity + stretched my ability to see. Here are just a few that captured my imagination by Ellen Gallagher, Norman Lewis, @LornaSimpson, @TheasterGates, Jack Whitten, Gerhard Richter, Lee Krasner, Diego Rivera + Mark Rothko.😍

name: 2019-09-13 01.10.53 2131416374661043027_tatemodern.jpg
text: Dóra MaurerWhite Cube Bermondsey‪12 September 2019 – 3 November 2019‬An exhibition of the trailblazing Hungarian artist Dóra Maurer has just opened at White Cube Bermondsey. While Maurer is a master of many mediums, this show focuses specifically on paintings from three series: ‘Overlappings’, ‘Quod Libet’ and ‘IXEK’, all of which date from the late 1990s to 2013.Inhabiting a space between painting, sculpture and optical illusion, these works burst with energy and internal contradictions. Resistant to the constraints of geometric abstraction as embodied by Piet Mondrian, Maurer’s mind-bending compositions seem to detach themselves from the wall and float, contorted, in the air. The vibrancy and immediacy of her colour palette is a pure delight, especially in the areas of ‘overlap’ for which the artist carefully designs custom shades. In this regard, Maurer cites Josef Albers’ colour theory as a major inspiration - even translating his 1963 landmark study Interaction of Colour into Hungarian.Tate Modern is also currently showcasing Dóra Maurer in a year-long mini-retrospective. This is definitely worth checking out, particularly for a closer look at her graphic, photographic and filmic output.

name: 2019-09-13 02.14.07 2131448190856312799_tatemodern.jpg
text: Olafur Eliasson"The Weather Project"Tate Modern Londra, 2003Quando l’arte continua a essere mimesi della natura, ma si stacca dai supporti consueti ed entra nel nostro spazio, è ancora rappresentazione o diventa realtà? Senza aver la presunzione di poter ricreare il sole, Eliasson vuole studiare, come è stato detto a lungo, l’atmosfera, la luce, la nebbia etc etc, ma soprattutto vuole studiare l’uomo. O meglio, vuole che gli uomini studino se stessi. Come fare? Attraverso gli specchi appesi al soffitto, le persone possono guardarsi mentre guardano. Se vogliamo possiamo tirare in ballo Pistoletto ma il discorso è un po’ diverso perché in quel caso noi dovremmo dialogare con la figura dipinta attraverso i gesti. Qui non dialoghiamo con la pittura o con l’arte, dialoghiamo con un’atmosfera e con una natura artificiale. “La ragione per cui credo sia importante esercitarsi in fenomeni come questo della doppia prospettiva è che la nostra capacità di vedere noi stessi mentre guardiamo… oppure di valutare l’esperienza che stiamo vivendo uscendo fuori da noi stessi… questa particolare capacità è la stessa che ci rende in grado di capire noi stessi”.••••#olafureliasson #tatemodern #tatelondon #theweatherproject #sunset #experience #contemporaryartist #contemporaryart

name: 2019-09-13 05.27.51 2131545707601207859_tatemodern.jpg
text: The Ship of Tolerance is an international art project created by Ilya and Emilia Kabakov, two of the most celebrated artists of their generation and widely known for their large-scale installations. A retrospective of their work was held at Tate Modern in 2018.The Ship of Tolerance – a 60-foot long, hand-crafted wooden ship - is dedicated to educating and inspiring young people through the universal language of art. Its unique potency emerges via a curated workshop programme with primary schools, refugee groups and cultural organisations in which children paint silk panels to make sails for The Ship of Tolerance based on their discussion of diversity and the agency ideas gain through art.First launched in Egypt in 2005, The Ship of Tolerance has subsequently been created in various locations around the world including Venice, Havana, Moscow, New York and Rome. The project was awarded the prestigious Cartier Prize for the Best Art Project of the Year in 2010.For its presentation in London, the sails of The Ship of Tolerance have been made by children from forty London primary schools, from Great Ormond Street Hospital and from refugee centres in Birmingham, Leeds, Peterborough and Calais. #ilyaandemiliakabakov;#theshipoftolerancelondon2019;#tatemodern;#modernartprojects;#kabakovfoundation;#creativity;#peace

name: 2019-09-13 05.41.27 2131552557898033607_tatemodern.jpg
text: We love Pace artists Ilya and Emilia Kabakov’s The Ship of Tolerance; a beautiful project that promotes understanding of our differences and open-minded inclusivity. The Kabakovs involved local schoolchildren to create this epic work of art. Children of varying ethnic, social, and religious backgrounds contributed drawings on silk to form the sails of a 60-foot-long wooden ship, which ultimately became an intricate mosaic of diversity. The Ship of Tolerance was unveiled on September 5th in London on the River Thames near Tate Modern, as part of “Totally Thames 2019”, a celebration of the River Thames that features creative programming. Meanwhile, at Chicago’s Navy Pier, The Ship of Tolerance will also be displayed in association with the 2019 edition of EXPO CHICAGO. Uniquely, art always possesses the potential to encourage dialogue, and the fact that the Kabakovs have engaged impressionable young people in the actualization of The Ship of Tolerance is an act of hope in-and-of-itself. If you find yourself in London, England before November 8th, or in Chicago between September 17th and October 6th, this is a fabulous and important work of art to visit and reflect upon!  #shipoftolerance #kabakovs #kabakov #ilyakabakov #emiliakabakov #art #artist #publicart #london #england #uk #riverthames #theriverthames #totallythames2019 #chicago #expochicago #navypier #children #childrensart #drawing #boat #ship #silk #sails #diversity #inclusivity #equality #openmind #tatemodern #installation

text: How to get your art into Tate Modern!Ludwig meeting famous artist Ben Wilson. “Concentrating on my foto shoot on Millennium Bridge in front of the Tate today I heard a voice talking to me. I looked up into the big smile of Ben Wilson. In fact I was documenting his painted chewing gums on the pavement. Saw him here two years ago lying down doing his artwork. He is painting the flat sticking chewing gums around the world. In the video he reveals that his work is also inside the Tate Modern. Secretly. Sticking!”#great #art #fame #tatemodern #benwilsonchewinggumman #milleniumbridge #milleniumbridgelondon #no #compromise #living #for #the #art #start #small #bring #big #joy #london #photography #video #of #the #day

name: 2019-09-13 09.53.46 2131679547783122980_tatemodern.jpg
text: 🇬🇧 Tate modern museum. London, 31 de Enero, 2018. Unknown. .¿ is this ART ? Seeing this “piece of art” my first thought was that that wasn’t art, and how unfair it was that a talented artist could had displayed his art in his/her place. I Even took a picture to send as a joke of how nutritive in terms of art this was. I forgot to send it,and im glad i didnt, because it was one of the few pieces i remember marked me on this English museum and what inspired me the most on my hole journey through Europe. This white papers let us, the espectators, be the artists. This white papers are infinity. Every person who stands in front of them pictured different things. People from all over the world go to Tate modern in London. For me, a fashion designer from Uruguay, it was colours, i pictured a lot of colours. And i loved the idea of being the one who decides what to see.So i decide not to follow any more colour trends or “rules” for this season and make an all white collection for you to play with the artist inside of you. 🎨So maybe this piece is not art but it creates a lot of Artists. .#london #londoners #tate #museum #tatemodern #art #artist #design #inspiration #inspo #potd #concept story #trends #fashion #collection #designer #minimalism #minimalismo #minimal #white #lines #art

text: ❓Does this happen to you?❓ .You start to go through your vacation photos and you come across those family pictures that you’ve done during the first days of your holiday. And they provoke two emotions: happiness and nostalgia. Happiness because you remember the beauty of those first vacation days, when your entire trip is still waiting for you 🥰 and nostalgia, because now, at this moment, it is all over.😢.It happens to me all the time. And it also happened last night while I was transferring our last travel photos to my computer. .Does it happen to you?.Here we are at Tate Modern in London.💖 #momtags #familyvacation ..... 📷 Follow me on @itsmomtags for more lovely pics!📷

text: Since Pre-Raphaelitism’s debut, its criticism has been marked by contradictions so extreme that it is difficult to believe critics are discussing the same movement. The movement is at once childish and pornographically adult; radical and conservative; respectful towards women and scornful of them. ————————————————————————The Tate’s 1984 major Pre-Raphaelite show was reviewed in the New Statesman as ‘Mrs. Thatcher’s Neo-Victorian Age’ while the Sunday Telegraph was disgusted by its bohemianism and ‘druggy’ muses.Where nineteenth-century critics initially attacked the movement for its realism, twentieth and twenty-first-century haters dislike its symbolism and fantasy.————————————————————————What do you think, do you love or hate Pre-Raphaelites, and why? name: 2019-09-13 18.45.53 2131947366828228439_tatemodern.jpg
text: "I cannot think of my work as entirely my work. In a sense, I'm only a transmitter" Panayiotis Vassilakis (Takis).⠀⠀Takis is one of the ground-breaking and original artists to date. In his work, he explored, for the first time, the possibilities of electromagnetism.⠀⠀We visited Takis' exhibition at the Tate Modern, London, and saw his beautiful sculptures, suspended metal objects in space using magnets. Seeing these sculptures, we couldn't stop thinking about leadership and purpose or a "calling," as some may say.⠀⠀Often we are encouraged to find our purpose or "calling" in life: the reason we are here in this world; the reason we do what we do; why we wake up in the morning. These sculptures reminded us that calling and purpose are just like magnets. They pull you to them - firmly. You may try to avoid it, but it will always be energy that captivates, attracts, and pulls you. How often do you read about professionals who left what they were doing to pursue their "real" calling? How often do you think about it yourself?⠀⠀These magnets made us think about leaders and purpose. Can a leader be a magnet? ⠀Passing on energy, or shall I say, purpose, is the role of business leaders today. "I'm only a transmitter," said Takis and leaders are transmitters of their companies' mission. They are the ones who set the vision and open the possibilities, but at the same time, they need to transfer this electromagnetic power of purpose to their teams. ⠀⠀At The Artian, we see our purpose as bringing back the Renaissance Thinking in business; starting a new conversation that eliminates the artificial barrier between disciplines, and fostering a holistic approach that pushes the organization forward - but really forward. ⠀⠀So what is your calling? What is your company's purpose? ⠀⠀⠀#takis #PanayiotisVassilakis #tate #tatemodern #leadership #purpose #art⠀#magnetism #magnet

It is utterly magical, and testament to Ólafur Elíasson’s creativity and talent for creating beautifully surreal works that are a joy to lose yourself in.

name: 2019-09-14 01.57.21 2132164534834615980_tatemodern.jpg
text: At long, long last I finally opted for a @tate membership because lbh, Tate Modern is always one of the very first stops I make every time I’m in the city. I stopped through to check out the two exhibitions on at the moment, @studioolafureliasson as well as the PHENOMenaaaaal TAKIS @takisfoundation exhibition. At first they feel so markedly different, yet in many ways it’s just that both artists have taken different approaches to similar concepts — I recommend checking out Takis *after* Olafur Eliasson’s ‘In Real Life,’ basically so you can calm the heck down after what feels a little bit like spectacle. But that’s also exactly what I expect and want from an Eliasson exhibition, sooo.... Eliasson has a go-big-or-go-home approach (which in itself can be a little exhausting) to many of the same ideas that the complementary Takis exhibition also addresses: body, movement, presence (or lack thereof?) and environment. Takis, in the other hand, is an inviting, almost meditative alternative. Both are absolutely worth checking out, especially if you like lots of shiny, moving things, and getting mildly freaked out in enclosed spaces with limited visibility before going to marvel at electromagnetic and light sculpture and experience a little bit of true tension. 🧲.....#tate #olafureliasson #inreallife #tatemodern #takis #exhibitions #museum #museumvisit #london #travel #arttravel #modernart #contemporaryart #contemporarysculpture #artandexperience #installationart #installation #art #kaleidoscope #light #sound #video #body #climatechange #museumselfie #fog

name: 2019-09-14 02.03.15 2132167507582973999_tatemodern.jpg
text: The Olafur Eliason show at the Tate Modern is spectacular... Brought me back to my time in Reykjavik & in '97. Wild in every way. Giant walls of reindeer moss, kaleidoscopic windows to the outside, and some super fun interactive light pieces and sensory installations. Not sure if it was the sugar water fog or light but it's properly uplifting. Amazing room full of studio  models too... I could've spent all day there alone. And inspirational climate, social, architectural & collaborative work... The guy's a genius@ashleykelloff#olafureliasson #olafureliassonretrospective #tatemodern

name: 2019-09-14 02.48.37 2132190335928081132_tatemodern.jpg
text: I don’t have any bookish photos to share today so I am going to share some art with you.  I like going to look at art, it gets me out of my routine and fills me with awe, and that has to be good for mental health.  So here’s #keithharing #yvesklein #olafureliasson #vangogh #martincreed.  I usually go to these places on my own, it’s been found that people who look at art on their own spend longer looking at it and have a deeper emotional reaction to it, and that makes sense to me.  Not many people want to spend 30 mins in the #rothko room at the Tate modern to do #slowart but it is so rare that we get the time to just sit and take in the feelings that art evokes within us.  #artstagram #artlove #artlover #modernart #tatemodern #artgeek #artnerd

name: 2019-09-14 04.24.01 2132238354871520730_tatemodern.jpg
text: I was waiting for 2 years to have this polaroid to mark the culmination of this project! A recreation of a photo that went down in history. Swipe to see it, and how we got paparazzi’ed 😁 😅Big thanks to @iggstamatic who captured the moment...It humbled me and the artist, actor - James Dean of this project - Jules Chan, that we got to capture so many of the private moments that the public eyes wouldn’t otherwise see. I got a peak behind the curtain into the routines, struggles and the highs of everyday life of an actor that’s establishing himself. I got to see his private family life, something that played a big part in shaping his character. Sometimes when explaining the project to others, Jules himself would say that I got to see more of his life than a girlfriend would. That made me happy. Suck on that, girlfriends!! Just kidding 😆 The project brought us closer together, like it did Dennis and James. I gained a brother 🖤........#art #csm #ual #tate #tatemodern #tatestaffbiennale #insidejob #polaroid #polaroidphotography #photography #actor #actorslife #jamesdean #dennisstock #life #polaroidproject #interactiveart #timeline #homage

The new commission is an audio-visual installation with a guided tour that describes an imagined land, associated with the clichés related to the image of latin american culture. The artwork can be seen until November 10th.Tate Liverpool presenta la instalación de larga escala de la artista Sol Calero (b. 1982, Caracas, Venezuela) intitulada “El Autobús“. La nueva comisión es ina instalación audio visual con un tour guiado que describe una tierra imaginaria, associada con los clichés relacionados con a cultura latino americana. name: 2019-09-14 09.11.04 2132382834736228432_tatemodern.jpg
text: 🇬🇧 Tate modern museum, 31 de enero, 2018. ¿Es o no es arte? Al ver esto  mi primer pensamiento fue que no era arte, que no comunicaba nada y hasta me pareció injusto para el talentoso artista que podría estar exponiendo en su lugar. Termine probando cuan errada estabaal volver a ver la foto tiempo despues, ya que fue una de las obras que mas me marcó del Tate modern y fue la que mas me inspiro por todo mi viaje en Europa.Estos cuadros blancos nos permiten a nosotros,los espectadores, ser los artistas. Estos cuadros blancos son infinitos. Gente de todo el mundo va a visitar este museo inglés a diario. A mi me genero imaginarme muchos colores, y ame la idea de ser yo quien decida que ver. Seguramente a otra persona de otro pais, cultura y con otro estado de animo le pudo generar otra imagen. Inspirada en este momento decidi no seguir tendencias de color a la hora de diseñar esta nueva coleccion y crear una coleccion blanca, un lienzo en blanco, para que ustedes, los espectadores; jueguen con el artista que tienen adentro. 🎨Capaz esta obra es considerada arte, capaz no, es muy subjetivo; pero lo que es seguro es que genera muchos artistas...#london #londoners #tate #museum #tatemodern #art #artist #design #inspiration #inspo #potd #concept story #trends #fashion #collection #designer #minimalism #minimalismo #minimal #white #lines #art

name: 2019-09-14 17.00.41 2132619203823553739_tatemodern.jpg
text: The pre-Raphaelites Brotherhood was formed in 1848, it was the first modern art movement Britain, the "Victorian Avant-Garde" of a sort. The pre-Raphaelite artists were radical in their ways of looking, viewing their subjects with intense psychological attention. That pre-Raphaelite super-realism was achieved through meticulous attention to detail. The artists preferred painting outside the studio, the strange and often shocking candour of their vision exaggerated by the effects of natural light.The brotherhood was wonderfully wilful and obsessive. In the middle 1850s, Holman Hunt spent two years working in the Holy Land. The weirdest and most controversial painting he returned with was The Scapegoat. The background had been painted in situ on the shores of the Dead Sea, site of the city of abominations, Sodom, while the goat itself was posed back in Jerusalem, standing in a tray of salt crystals and the authentic Dead Sea mud. Hunt's complex symbolism bemused and angered people.What do you think about this Super Realism?To book our Walk Through British Art, please visit our website https://www.nejasartwalks.com/british-art-at-tate-britainor email us info@nejasartwalks.com#preRaphaelites #JohnEverettMillais #millais #victorianengland #victorianart #victorianmasculinity #art #londonart #Londonartgallery #artmuseum #artdaily  #painting #londonartwalks #nejasartwalks #britishart #artinspiration #londra #londres #artist #tatebritain #tatemodern #visitlondon #WilliamHolmanHunt

name: 2019-09-14 17.45.06 2132641547618589974_tatemodern.jpg
text: Yesterday I was lucky enough to spend a Friday night in my favorite Moscow museum @garagemca. On Fridays there's an opportunity to get there for free (from 5pm to 8pm) and this free admission is sponsored by a Japanese brand UNIQLO, one of the partners of Garage Museum. On other days you need to pay 500 rub to get to an exhibition. The Tretyakov Gallery and the Pushkin Museum also charge 500 rub for an entry. And I suppose it's quite expensive, especially for a Russian person/family with an average income, visiting Moscow on holidays. Meanwhile in London most of museums are free and this free admission is funded by the government. It has become an accepted fact of cultural life there since 2001. I think it's one of the best investments a government can make into a nation. So it's no surprise that London is one of the world's capitals of culture and the best place in the world for communication (as Boris Johnson said, and I totally agree with him here). While in Russia the lack of knowledge about art (especially modern art) is still so obvious and a lot of people are just intimidated to go to museums and art galleries not only because the price puts them off, but also because they feel they are not qualified enough to appreciate art.In the photos: A few books I bought in London museums at very affordable prices. 📚Me in the British Museum and Tate Modern. 🗿🎨

name: 2019-09-14 18.53.44 2132676099809677185_tatemodern.jpg
text: Tate ModernOlafur Eliasson-In Real Life11 July 2019 – 5 January 2020Olafur Eliasson，丹麥出生的冰島藝術家，他的裝置作品多與自然議題相聯結，擅長運用光,氣體,顏色挑戰觀者的感知能力。1993年的作品”Beauty”透過噴灑細密雨滴，架設燈光產生折射，一道彩虹漂浮在水簾上伴隨著觀者不同角度隨之波動；1997年的”Room for One Colour”，他安裝了黃色單頻燈光照亮整體空間，光線會影響觀眾的視覺，在復古暖黃的空間裡，不論照像或是觀看任何事物，只能接收兩種顏色：黃色和黑色，這次Olafur Eliasson也在Tate Modern 電梯裡裝置了暖黃燈，置身在其中非常的有趣。此次展覽最喜歡的一件作品是2010年創作的”Your Blind Passenger”整個空間注滿甜甜的氣體，同樣以單頻燈光打在充滿霧氣的空間，人在行走的過程，視覺,味覺,嗅覺,都受到了影響，唯獨可以用觸覺接觸壁面，確定方向他的裝置作品在博物館裡重新體現大自然的美，讓觀者運用感知去體驗作品與空間的關係#Yu💋ArtExhibitionReview #OlafurEliasson#TateModern#uk#London#ArtExhibition #environmentissues #tate

text: When we were both living in Warsaw and hanging around like two best friends, people didn’t believe we are brothers. They always say we look so different. And very often they couldn’t guess which one is older, even there is 4 years difference between us.▫️Yes, we are very different personalities, but at the same time we are very similar, shaped by the same house we grew up. It is the only person who understands some nuance no one else does.▫️We always laugh from the same jokes. And he is always there to support me. He is the most stubborn and at the same time the kindest soul I know.▫️Today it is the birthday of this special guy. Have another beautiful year on that crazy planet. I'm grateful that you are!▫️#happybirthday #brother #virgo #tatemodern #contemporaryart #modernart #art #olafureliasson #inreallife

name: 2019-09-14 22.17.23 2132778604587880346_tatemodern.jpg
text: Drawing on Rudolf Stingel's Untitled is fun and totally addictive. ‘Rudolph Stingel’s Untitled 1993 consists of a wall entirely covered with orange carpeting. Viewers are invited to mould and sculpt the thick pile of the carpet, offering an experience that engages both sight and touch. Stingel challenges artistic conventions by exchanging paint on canvas for carpet mounted directly onto the wall and allowing the viewer to make their own marks on the surface. The result is a work of art that relies on an audience for its completion, undermining traditional notions of artistic authorship.’ #tatemodern#rudolphstingel#londonlove

text: ‘Verb 2 Believe, Believe’ (‘Colours’ series, 2018)‘COLOURS’ series is a comment on NUANCES of the language, AS WELL AS the nuance of ‘colours’...language can be equally USEFUL=USELESS...and I still, (steal) find it FUNDAMENTAL even if we all borrow the words we speak. ‘COLOURS’ is one of my comments on ‘THE ABSOLUTE POSSIBILITY OF DIS UNDERSTANDING’ which is not about ‘Misunderstanding’ it is about being understood in ways we do not really mean or maybe we do mean, ITS ABOUT THE CHANCE OF PLAYING finite and infinite GAMES. @artspace Reyzorro#contemporaryart#reyzorro @artspace #whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #NewMediaArt #fashion #art#tategallery

name: 2019-09-15 01.25.33 2132873308801997753_tatemodern.jpg
text: 🇬🇧ロンドン3日目&4日目．3日目WellingboroughDr.Martensの本社に行くためにロンドンから特急列車に一時間ほど乗って、Wellingboroughという街へ。車窓からの景色は牛や羊、丘の上にポツンと一軒家など絵本のような世界だった。．Wellingboroughからバス停まで15分ほど。かなりの田舎町でアジア人は皆無。何しに来たん？という感じでチラチラ見られる。降りるバス停で後ろから御婦人が「マーチンに行くならここで降りなさい、来た道を戻って左へ」と教えてくれる。優しくて涙。．made in Englandを買う。マーチンを履くならどうしても一足はEngland製が欲しかった。．帰りのバス停の時刻表が難解で、ただ待つ。減っていくバッテリー。かなり不安になりながらも一時間半待つ。ようやく来たバスに乗り込み安堵する。．ロンドンに着いた頃ちょうどディナーの時間だったのでSt.Pancras駅近くのアイリッシュパブへ。念願のギネスビールとフィッシュ&チップス。3分の2ほど食べた頃に火災警報機がなり係員に追い出され他の客とともに店を出た。．ロンドンの美しい街並みで軽く酔い、気分良く帰路につく。．4日目セントポール大聖堂とテートモダンを見る。．#uk #kingsroad #viviennewestwood #sloanesquare #aldgateeast #westminster #海外留学 #英国 #英国留学 #unitedkingdom #イギリス旅行 #英国旅行 #旅行記 #旅スタグラム #英国生活 #欧州旅行 #ヨーロッパ旅行 #テートモダン #tate #tatemodern #stpaul #セントポール大聖堂 #drmartens #Wellingborough #🇬🇧

text: Frances Stark, ‘Behold Man!’ (2013). It’s a self portrait showing the artist surrounded by appropriated images of men including a Sylvia Sleigh portrait of male nude. Stark responds to the stereotype of the active male and the passive female, casting herself in the central role. I remember this having a startling presence when presented as part of our Sylvia Sleigh exhibition at Tate Liverpool in 2013. #francesstark #sylviasleigh #tatecollection #tatemodern

name: 2019-09-15 05.50.12 2133006513631665193_tatemodern.jpg
text: ‘Verb 2 Fly, Fly’ (‘Colours’ series, 2018)‘COLOURS’ series is a comment on NUANCES of the language, AS WELL AS the nuance of ‘colours’...language can be equally USEFUL=USELESS...and I still, (steal) find it FUNDAMENTAL even if we all borrow the words we speak. ‘COLOURS’ is one of my comments on ‘THE ABSOLUTE POSSIBILITY OF DIS UNDERSTANDING’ which is not about ‘Misunderstanding’ it is about being understood in ways we do not really mean or maybe we do mean, ITS ABOUT THE CHANCE OF PLAYING finite and infinite GAMES. Collected  @grahammcreynolds @mssociety @merkle @artspace Reyzorro#contemporaryart#reyzorro @artspace #whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #NewMediaArt #fashion #art

text: PROYECTO DE MUSEO SOBRE CASTILLO EN PONFERRADAContinúan las obras !!! Inauguración: 9.10.2019 (Capicúa del año !!!)PONS FERR ART 1082 . 2019“El puente en el Arte”Santalla & StrartS y QuinSan han creado la Asociación de Museos Virtuales, cuyo fin es que todos los pueblos, independientemente de su población, puedan disponer de un museo de arte.El lema es: NINGÚN PUEBLO SIN MUSEO.Los tres primeros museos ya se han inaugurado en Lapuebla de Labarca, San Juan de la Mata y Madrid. El próximo será  en Ponferrada y después en Vitoria, Alovera, Arganza, Azuqueca, Sancti Petri, Trillo, Laguardia, Guadalajara, Elciego, Yebra, Logroño, La Puebla de Ponferrada,.... MUSEUM PROJECT ON CASTLE IN PONFERRADAThe works continue !!!Inauguration: 9.10.2019 (Capicúa of the year !!!)PONS FERR ART 1082. 2019“The bridge in Art”Santalla & StrartS and QuinSan have created the Association of Virtual Museums, whose purpose is that all peoples, regardless of their population, can have an art museum.The motto is:NO PEOPLE WITHOUT MUSEUM.The first three museums have already opened in Lapuebla de Labarca, San Juan de la Mata and Madrid. The next one will be in Ponferrada and then in Vitoria, Alovera, Arganza, Azuqueca, Sancti Petri, Trillo, Laguardia, Guadalajara, Elciego, Yebra, Logroño, La Puebla de Ponferrada, .... #reinasofiamuseum #museodelprado #caixaforum #museothyssen #hermitagemuseum #whitneymuseum #centrepompidou  #nationalgallery  #moma  #museedorsay #louvre #met #salvadordalimuseum #britishmuseum  #tatemodern #guggenheim #nycart #brooklynmuseum #lacmamuseum #gemaldegalerie #artinstitutechicago #ufizzi  #louvreabudhabi #galleriaborghese #gettymuseum #yaleartgallery #sfmoma #nationalgalleryofart #altepinakothek #rijksmuseum

text: Londres 2019. Muy pequeña entre obras tan grandes. El arte moderno me apasiona. Disciplinas como el audiovisual me atrapan. Sin embargo, tengo que reconocer que me cuesta comprender algunas obras. También pienso que el tiempo es el gran juez y sólo él sabe cuáles de ellas pasarán a ser significativas.Por cierto, os voy a colgar dos obras en las stories para que veáis de lo que hablo. Me han parecido ambas geniales.Good night #tatemodernMe duelen los 👣👣👣

name: 2019-09-15 11.37.47 2133181453580454290_tatemodern.jpg
text: ‘Untitled’ (‘Colours’ series, 2018)‘COLOURS’ series is a comment on NUANCES of the language, AS WELL AS the nuance of ‘colours’...language can be equally USEFUL=USELESS...and I still, (steal) find it FUNDAMENTAL even if we all borrow the words we speak. ‘COLOURS’ is one of my comments on ‘THE ABSOLUTE POSSIBILITY OF DIS UNDERSTANDING’ which is not about ‘Misunderstanding’ it is about being understood in ways we do not really mean or maybe we do mean, ITS ABOUT THE CHANCE OF PLAYING finite and infinite GAMES. Collected  @grahammcreynolds @mssociety @merkle @artspace Reyzorro#contemporaryart#reyzorro @artspace #whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #NewMediaArt #fashion #art

name: 2019-09-15 11.38.56 2133182037014966803_tatemodern.jpg
text: #테이트모던#목표_브런치의명가#브런치의정석#하반기에는더욱풍성하게#추석연휴D_1#생각_기록 #미래의인재상..외식업의 휴가와 명절은참으로 짧고 바쁩니다..직원들도 모두 휴무에 나와 수고를 하고 있는어제 오늘입니다:))물론 법적휴무 일수를 어떤 수단으로든지켜주고는 있지만.. 제때 즐길 수 없는점이 있네요...그만큼 열심히 남들 쉴때, 휴가철에저희는 그만큼의 서비스로 보상해드리기위해 노력하고 있으니 조금만 더 예쁘게바라봐주시면 너무도 감사합니다🙇🏻‍♀️.아직은 사회초년생들도 많고 20대들이많은 회사라 태도들이 옛스럽지 않다고 여기실 수있겠지만.. 이 젊은이들도 나름 스스로의방식으로 노력하고 있는것 같습니다...요즘 사회에 감정노동이니, 열정페이,헬조선, 흙수저이니 등이런 단어들이 때로는 20대 사회초년생들에게 자기합리화를 가져다주는게 아닌지조금은 걱정도 스럽습니다...대한민국 자영업자들은 이보다 더한 고충을 가지고 버는돈의 40-50%는 세금을내고 높은 금리의 대출이자를 정산하며한달한달을 살아가는 우리들이지만..아마도 자기창업의 꿈일 가지고 있는우리 20대들은 그런 고충 아마도 모르겠죠🙂.그러다보니 이런 외식업은 프라이드와 전문성이너무도 중요하다는 것을 꼭 이야기하고싶기에.. 저희 회사는 매우 직원들에게엄격하고 까다로운 것 같습니다...고객분들이 받고자 하는 서비스와 품질을기대 이상으로 뛰어넘어야 하는데.. 이 말을 하는 즉슨“사장의 갑질과 잔소리”가 되는 것 같다는생각을 현장에서 너무도 많이 하는것 같습니다..파트너들의 이력서에는 모두 공통적인 부분이“배우러왔다” 이지만.. 아카데미도아닌 실무현장에 스스로들이 정말 배울 생각을 하고 왔는지 의문에 들때가 많기도하는것 같습니다.정말 학교처럼 A-Z까지를 다 일일히떠먹여주듯 수동적인 자세로 업무를 진행하는사람들도 간혹 있기도 합니다. 여기는 직장이지학교가 아닌데 말이지요..스스로 발품을 팔아가며 조직내에서 찾아다니며 배워야 하는 일들이 많은 외식업의 특성을 모를 수도 있겠다싶습니다...진짜 배워야 하는것 오너들의 마인드와 철학.그들의 노하우가 어떻게 이루어지는지어떤 과정이었는지를 궁금해하고 질문하고세밀하게 보아야 하는데..실상 겉보여지는 것에만 운운하고있지 않은지 사실 걱정도 큽니다..저의 목표는 확고합니다.타협하지 않는 자연주의 브런치와 다이닝본질에 철저하게 집중하는 요리. 그리고감성의 서비스.아마 죽는 날까지 식당을 운영한다면저는 분명 이 말을 똑같이 써내려갈 자신이 있습니다...그래서 브랜드의 생명력을 불어줄파트너들의 옥석을 열심히 가려내고찾아가고 있습니다..그런데 이미 다 알고 있고정확히 미래가 보이는 것도 소름돋는일은듯 합니다..개인적 판단하지만 연륜의 시야는 결코 배신하지않는 것 같습니다...조금더 노력하고 본인 스스로의 직무와업무 본질에 타협하지 않는 사람을찾아가고 브랜드를 함께 성장시키고 싶습니다...제가 2015년부터 이를 악물고만들고 지켜온 이 소중한 브랜드를반드시 힘을 모아 함께 나아갈 수 있는그런 열정적인 인재 _요즘 채용사이트에구직을 할때 열정이란 단어를 쓰는 것도부적합한 내용이라 자동차단이 되는 시대입니다_ 진짜 그들에게 회사 지분을 맡기고 나누어줄 수 있는 주인이 되는 외식브랜드를만드는게 저의 일생의 꿈이자 목표입니다..저는 한국에서 태어나고 자랐지만나름 서구적 마인드를 가졌다고 생각합니다.회사의 주인이 될 수 있는 리더는 반드시 능력있고 실력있는 노력형 인재가성장해야 한다고 생각합니다..그래야만“브런치의 명가” 라는 타이틀을 내걸더라도 부끄럽지 않을 것 같다는생각을 하는 오너의 마지막 연휴의고민입니다..요즘같은 세상에 제가 너무 무리한 욕심이 아니길 바래봅니다..품격있는 요리와 서비스를 고객에게내어준다는 것 자체가 명예로운 일이니까요✨.#인재를리더로성장시키기위해#오너가고민해야할것들#무엇이정답일까?

text: “Pietre Numerarie”, numerary stones, scultura bassorilievo, Villa Nobel Sanremo, 2016-2019 #tizianobellomi.l'azione minima di una numerazione progressiva che si protrae da diversi anni, una numerazione ma anche una catalogazione, la trasformazione di un oggetto anonimo in un particolare oggetto, in questo concetto risiede la mia operazione artistica. the minimal action of a progressive numbering that has been going on for several years, a numbering but also a cataloging, the transformation of an anonymous object into a particular object, in this concept lies my artistic operation.@arteam.associazione . . #artconsultant #landart #collecteurs #artadvisory #contemporarysculpture #artecontemporanea #installationart #whitecube #artcollector #artfair #artcurator #artgallery #artbasel #berlingallery #contemporaryart #frieze #delphianopencall #londongallery #londonart #newyorkgallery #postminimal #postwarart #tatemodern #numberingart #sculpture #artberlin #artdealer @espoarte

text: Nada mejor que un domingo lluvioso para recordar aquel viaje y esos columpios que nos dieron tanto juego ❤️Gracias @marfatravel de nuevo!!!COLUMPIOS EN LA TATE MODERNLos columpios,  una nueva instalación artística de un colectivo llamado Superflex, compuesto por tres artistas daneses que producen arte subversivo y crean instalaciones artísticas en las que el juego y la diversión juegan un papel muy importante.La instalación artística cuenta con 3 partes y entrando por el lateral oeste del museo encontraréis, bajando por la gran rampa del Turbine Hall, un gran bola metálica plateada moviéndose en forma de péndulo y en el suelo un enorme tapete de colores de 770 metros cuadrados en el que os podéis acostar a mirar el péndulo. Después ya se ven todos los columpios, los cuales son para tres personas cada uno y en los que os podéis subir sin ningún problema con vuestros amigos y familiares o, como lo pretenden los artistas, con completos desconocidos.La instalación artística Superflex, con todos sus columpios, la pudimos disfrutar en la Tate Modern desde el 3 de octubre del 2017 hasta el 2 de abril del 2018.LONDRES/DICIEMBRE 2017🍃🍃🍃🍃🍃🍃🍃#tatemodern#travel#travellondon #londres🇬🇧 #londres2017 #london_city_photo #london_enthusiast

name: 2019-09-15 18.24.26 2133386132964468417_tatemodern.jpg
text: Work (1852–1865) is a painting by Ford Madox Brown that is generally considered to be his most important achievement. The painting attempts to portray, both literally and analytically, the totality of the Victorian social system and the transition from a rural to an urban economy. The picture depicts a group of so-called "navvies" digging up the road to build an underground tunnel. It is typically assumed that this was part of the extensions of London's sewerage system, which were being undertaken to deal with the threat of typhus and cholera.The workers are in the centre of the painting. On either side of them are individuals who are either unemployed or represent the leisured classes. Behind the workers are two wealthy figures on horseback, whose progress along the road has been halted by the excavations.The painting also portrays an election campaign, evidenced by posters and people carrying sandwich boards with the name of the candidate "Bobus". A poster also draws attention to the potential presence of a burglar.The setting is an accurate depiction of The Mount on Heath Street in Hampstead, London, where a side road rises up above the main road and runs alongside it.To book our Walk Through British Art, please visit our website https://www.nejasartwalks.com/british-art-at-tate-britainor email us info@nejasartwalks.com#preRaphaelites #JohnEverettMillais #millais #victorianengland #victorianart #victorianmasculinity #art #londonart #Londonartgallery #artmuseum #artdaily  #painting #londonartwalks #nejasartwalks #britishart #artinspiration #londra #londres #artist #tatebritain #tatemodern #visitlondon #WilliamHolmanHunt #FordMadoxBrown

text: PARVIZ TANAVOLIParviz Tanavoli was born in Tehran in 1937. Upon graduating from the Brera Academy of Milan in 1959, he taught sculpting at the Tehran College of Decorative Arts, and from 1961 - 1963 he thought at the Minneapolis College of Art and Design. He then returned to Iran and assumed the head of sculpting department at the University of Tehran, a position he held for 18 years until 1979, when he retired from his teaching duties.His work has been displayed at the British Museum - London, the Grey Art Gallery - New York University, the Isfahan City Center - Iran, Metropolitan Museum - New York, Minneapolis Institute of Art - Minneapolis, Olympic Park - Seoul, S. Korea, Qatar National Museum, Royal Museum - Jordan, Royal Scottish Museum - UK, the Museum of Modern Art - Vienna, Museum of Modern Art - New York, Walker Art Center - Minneapolis, Shiraz University - Iran, Tate Modern - London and in numerous other prestigious venues around the world.#parviztanavoli #sculptor #artist #art #culture #iran #contemporaryart #art #iranianartist #irancontemporary #artgallery #artwork #painting #dubai #exhibition #marbella #resort #gallery #middeleast #paris #tatemodern #saatchigallery #museum #moca #tmoca #britishmuseum #tatemodern

The modules support panes of colour effect filter glass; an LED lamp at the centre of the sphere shines out to project a #colourful pattern of light and shadow onto the surroundings. Classic Eliasson at his finest!
