name: 2019-09-15 22.08.30 2133498904403091436_tatemodern.jpg
text: 🍀 By left hand fingertips, various material, @tate 2018.🍀 ..🔴 > CRITICISM, THE FIGHT, THE FUTURE: LUCA ROSSI (5 october @galleriasix curated by @giacinto.di )... In the Italian contemporary art scene there is a figure of considerable interest. Luca Rossi–artist/ collective, critic, curator, and blogger–is a controversial personality who works in anonymity, as some kind of Anonymous of the Art System. In Luca Rossi’s philosophy, the ego no longer exists because anyone can be Luca Rossi, at the same time that the “critical process”, the virtual space of the Internet, and the real context no longer have boundaries and blend into one. Scroll down this page. ..Today individuals experience a sort of “non-experience” in the sense that they spend most of their time surfing the “network”, producing a “new memory-without memory” or a “passive and a-critical assimilation” into the system. Luca Rossi knows this well. He constantly reminds us of the history of art and ideas, of our past, of what it means to be critical and active, struggling to preserve one’s own authenticity and originality in the great McDonald that is our contemporary world...Many curators and artists, both in Italy and Europe, have been following Luca’s work with great excitement. By now Luca is considered the only critical voice that “stands out” in the current Italian landscape...It is worrisome that Luca’s work has yet to be recognized by institutions and organizations, despite receiving the acknowledgement of the public and many curators and artists. This says a lot about what the value that the Italian system places on the “real artist”. The Italian contemporary landscape has been dragging itself down for more than 10 years, producing artists who “copy and paste”, endless repetitions of projects signed by the same names, and decreeing the end of contemporary art...#mayyouliveininterestingtimes#biennalearte2019#lucarossilab#mauriziocattelan #arthurjafa #victoryisnotanoption #stolentoilet #tatemodern

text: Dora MaurerDisplay @tateImages: 'What can one do with a paving stone?'1971 (www.reactfeminism.org)I was particularly excited to see this on display as I remember how inspired by it I was as a young art student. My long suffering father was talked into an outing with a bright orange cushion on a Sunday morning. He had to stand in various locations with the cushion whilst I took photographs! So I have a particular affection for this piece. 💕Two pieces from the Displacements(System Drawing) series.1971 and 1976 (personal photographs taken@tate)#doramaurer#systemsart#tate#tatemodern#abstraction#series#femaleartist#womenartist#hungarianartist

name: 2019-09-15 22.55.10 2133522389651995991_tatemodern.jpg
text: This really doesn’t do the experience any justice, but ‘Your blind passenger’ aka the fog tunnel was an intense experience. The fog and colour of the light seem to intensify each other. If you look straight ahead you can’t see anything to the sides making the space seem vast. After a while the intense yellow light means that when you blink you momentarily see only purple. Such an experience from such a simple idea. Perfect in execution. #olafureliasson #fog #light #colour #intense #tatemodern

name: 2019-09-16 00.21.09 2133565674408073061_tatemodern.jpg
text: ㅤㅤ먼 미래와, 뜬구름 잡는 상상을 하는 건 생각보다 도움이 되는 것 같다.요즘 내가 하는 상상은 10년 후의 것들!ㅤㅤ아마도 내 나이 또래의 친구들이 모두 필드에서 열심히 뛰고 있을 시기, 나 또한 나이나 경력에 의심받지 않을 시기, 처음 해보는 것이 지금보다는 적어질 시기, 좋아하지 않은 사람과는 더이상 마주치지않고 있을 시기, 좋은 사람은 더더욱 가까워졌을 시기. 뭐 이런 거.ㅤㅤ"대단한 사람이 되겠어!" 라는 것 말고,지금의 매일과는 아주 달라져있을- 미래의 사소한 일상에 대한 기대감. 오늘보다 더 나은 내일이라는 유치한 문구가 요즘은 되게 희망적으로 느껴진다니까? #하유리관찰기

name: 2019-09-16 01.35.53 2133603285293302486_tatemodern.jpg
text: heopened me uplike a book& poured the poetryback intome. .- my personal pen & paper.—————————— @ladybookmad.—————————having been a singer most of my young adult life, i’d always felt drawn to lyrics and poetry. i felt a kinship and siblinghood in it — being an only child, poems and stories were who kept me company most of my life. but my written form never ventured longer than a dabble into the occasional poem myself, as i never felt i found the pocket when it came to writing poetry. however, this summer i’ve been secretly experimenting with poetry. and although i still think my poetry skills need a lot of cultivation, it’s been a fun new medium through with to express myself. not sure if it’ll ever get shared beyond my own two eyes 👀 but flexing new muscles in the writer toolbox is always a learning experience 🧰 maybe i’ll start an anonymous poetry instagram (who has the time though, not sure that person is me lol).—————————photo: @jesyelyse | @jesysbooks.edit: @michellemgrondine | @tediously_brief.—————————camera: @canonusa EOS 5D Mark IV.lens: @canonusa EF 50mm f/1.8 STM Lens.app(s): @lightroom.—————————#tatemodern #aintbad #shootaesthetics #nowherediary #50mm #moodyports #filmvibes #classicsmagazine #lookslikefilm #bleachmyfilm #shadows #filmaesthetic #vintagemood #windowphotography #grainisgood #classicsmagazine #portsbycanon #analogvibes #visualpoetry #visualpoem #visualstorytelling.—————————#olafureliasson @studioolafureliasson exhibit at the @tate modern.—————————

name: 2019-09-16 02.16.11 2133623561836145066_tatemodern.jpg
text: Between Paris and Amsterdam I was supposed to be going to both Luxembourg and Bruges as originally planned.Instead, in Paris I got a bunch of what I'm gonna call "backpacker's fatigue" (or my ribs were playing up unsure). I was so tired all the time and I was considering quitting early and going home. So I did. Sort of.I still had to be in Amsterdam for the 19th as I have plans and it was the location that, of the three, I was most excited for. But I didn't fancy such a long, expensive stay.The detour I decided on was cheaper, more responsible and in the end the clear winner:Took a coach to London, saw some good friends over the weekend, saw NHS doctors who gave me a new stylin' splint (thank god) and after a few days relaxing at home organising my life, I went to Northern Ireland for a week to see a long term (12 years) childhood friend of mine at long last. We had a chill time, caught up and laughed about the past! ☺️ Here's an assortment of photos from my trip through including a visit to the Tate Modern and a comforting picture of home.#europe_vacations #europetravel #unitedkingdom #tatemodern #northernireland

name: 2019-09-16 02.42.10 2133636644228974181_tatemodern.jpg
text: The Ship of Tolerance, moored outside @thetatemodern, is an international art project created by Ilya and Emilia Kabakov.The Ship of Tolerance is dedicated to educating and inspiring young people.Children paint silk panels to make sails based on their discussion of diversity.The sails for the London installation of this wooden ship came from London primary schools, Great Ormond Street Hospital and from refugee centres in Birmingham, Leeds, Peterborough and Calais.

text: 🇬🇧ロンドン5日目．行きたいところに行ききったため、今日は気になる街を延々と散策。.Notting Hill Gate映画 ノッティングヒルの恋人の聖地。ピンクやラベンダー、水色に塗られた家が立ち並ぶゾーンと、ホワイト一色の高級住宅地がある場所。Sister Janeというブランドの実店舗があるので見てきた。.Oxford CircusOxford Roadというヨーロッパで一番買い物客が多い通り。高級ブランドはそんなにあるわけではないけど、ふらっと入れるお店がたくさん立ち並んでいた。感覚は渋谷に近いかも。TOPSHOPがかなり充実していた。地下二階にはTOPSHOPセレクトの個人ブランドも取り扱っていて見ていて飽きなかった。．Piccadilly Circusアフタヌーンティーのために。と思っていたら街並みが非常に美しい街だった。日曜だったのでホコ天になっており、至る所で生演奏が繰り広げられていた。．Covent Gardenマーケットが立ち並ぶ。多分友達と一緒に行くと楽しいところ。マイナーな化粧品屋の路面店も多々あって良かった。Melissaの店舗が映え映えだった。．明日からパリ入り。緊張する。．．#uk #kingsroad #viviennewestwood #sloanesquare #aldgateeast #westminster #海外留学 #英国 #英国留学 #unitedkingdom #イギリス旅行 #英国旅行 #旅行記 #旅スタグラム #英国生活 #欧州旅行 #ヨーロッパ旅行 #テートモダン #tate #tatemodern #stpaul #セントポール大聖堂 #drmartens #Wellingborough #oxfordcircus #nottinghill #sisterjane #afternoontea #🇬🇧

text: "Oh, the foes will riseWith the sleep still in their eyesAnd they'll jerk from their beds and think they're dreamin'But they'll pinch themselves and squealAnd know that it's for realThe hour when the ship comes inThen they'll raise their handsSayin' we'll meet all your demandsBut we'll shout from the bow your days are numberedAnd like Pharaoh's tribeThey'll be drownded in the tideAnd like Goliath, they'll be conquered"..('When the Ship Comes In', Bob Dylan)..The Ship of Tolerance moored outside Tate Modern for September..For its presentation in London, the sails of The Ship of Tolerance have been made by children from forty London primary schools, from Great Ormond Street Hospital and from refugee centres in Birmingham, Leeds, Peterborough and Calais..The Ship of Tolerance is an international art project created by Ilya and Emilia Kabakov. name: 2019-09-16 16.51.31 2134064138731835852_tatemodern.jpg
text: By the Canal..🎨 Painted by Wilhelm von Gegerfelt.Born: 9 November 1844, Gothenburg, Sweden.Died: 2 April 1920, Torekov, Sweden..🖼 Oil on canvas 65 x 93 cm..📝 Born in Gothenburg, Gegerfelt was the son the architect Victor von Gegerfelt (1817-1915)From 1861 to 1863, he studied at the Royal Danish Academy, at the Royal Swedish Academy from 1864 to 1867, and thereafter in Düsseldorf until 1872.He then went to Paris where he developed a new technique joining Alfred Wahlberg as one of the first Swedes to represent the Modern Breakthrough in Nordic art. He travelled to the north coast of France, to Italy and to England, painting landscapes of Venice's lagoons and the English chalk cliffs, in addition to scenes of summer evenings in Sweden.His works can be seen in the National Museum in Stockholm, in the Gothenburg Museum of Art and in Skagens Museum.Gegerfelt exhibited in Monaco from 1883 and won a silver medal at the Vienna exhibition the same year. In Paris, he sold his paintings to the Duke of Bassano as well as to Goupil & Cie.Gagerfelt spent his later life in the fishing village of Torekov in the south of Sweden..(Fig 2, 3, 4: Details)...#museum #moma #metmuseum #museedulouvre #britishmuseum #nationalgallery #museodelprado #vangoghmuseum #brooklynmuseum #artforum #artbasel #tatemodern #instamuseum #rijksmuseum #whitneymuseum #nationalgalleryofvictoria #nationalmuseum #gettymuseum #curator #graffiti #streetart #oilpainting #artwork #landscape #boat #wilhelmvongegerfelt #gothenburg #torekov #sweden #yourarttimes

text: Каким должно быть свадебное платье?Мечта каждой невесты - выглядеть изумительно на своей свадьбе. И чтобы этого добиться, необходимо правильно подобрать платье. Оно должно быть идеальным, но как не утонуть в этот огромном ассортименте, предполагаемом в свадебных салонах? Как подобрать именно ту модель, которая скроет все недостатки и подчеркнет достоинства? В этот сезон мне посчастливилось  познакомиться с настоящим профессионалом и просто прекрасным человеком  @kristinakomilfo таких свадебных платьев  как у Кристины в слоне очень сложно найти, изысканный ассортимент, каждая будущая невеста найдет то самое платье! Фотограф @artemy_fedoseev

name: 2019-09-16 18.18.13 2134107772874599885_tatemodern.jpg
text: This week we are going to shine some light on forgotten women artists.Rosa Brett (1829 –1882) was a Pre-Raphaelite painter and sister of landscape artist John Brett. Her diary entries record that though they collaborated together, a portion of Rosa's work was sold under her brother's name. Describing an evening when John's pupils came to visit, Rosa said, '[...] I had to make my escape not wishing anyone to see me working at the [picture entitled] Fungus as the work passes for John's.' Her artistic career was cut short by chronic illness and family demands. She used the pseudonym 'Rosarius' for a period when exhibiting. She never married and died aged 52.To book our Walk Through British Art, please visit our website https://www.nejasartwalks.com/british-art-at-tate-britainor email us info@nejasartwalks.com#preRaphaelites #JohnEverettMillais #millais #victorianengland #victorianart #rosabrett #art #londonart #Londonartgallery #artmuseum #artdaily  #painting #londonartwalks #nejasartwalks #britishart #artinspiration #londra #londres #artist #tatebritain #tatemodern #visitlondon #WilliamHolmanHunt #FordMadoxBrown #womenartists #womanartist #femaleartist #forgottenwomenartists

name: 2019-09-16 19.33.29 2134145648564617889_tatemodern.jpg
text: Oh London ... this week end I realised how much I have missed you - the beauty of the fierce British empire buildings, the Turner like sunsets on the Thames, the foxes and squirrels in the garden...It was a renewal of my love for this wonderful city. Because where else can you have a pyjamas party with a storyteller in a secret location? It was a special night not to be forgotten, organised and mis en scene by my marvellous @40winkslondon in @theconduitlondonI'm always a little sad when I leave, but London, I promise: I will have my time with you soon again. I'll be back to see your leaves go brown, feel the wind in my hair, and drink tea at the Wolsley.A special thanks to my Jeanne for the beautiful picture of the sunset 💗#london #davidcarter #portobellomarket #40winks #lovelondon #pyjamasparty #theconduit #tatemodern #bedtimestorynights #naughtytales #storyteller #londonnights #londondays #Thames #sunset #turner #thewolsley #friends #renewal #timeformyself #traceyemin #stpancras #art

text: Serene and beautiful this art is not!.Reveling in the depraved, the carnal and the misogynistic, the art of the Weimar Republic is often ugly and perhaps over-rated. But collectively, this is art that provides a thought-provoking record of a troubled and contradictory period.If you’re interested in reading more, my article ‘Magic Realism: The Art of Weimar Germany’ can be found by clicking the link in the bio (July 2019).George Grosz (1893 – 1959) Self-Portrait with Model in the Studio (1930-1937) © Estate of George Grosz, Princeton, N.J. 2018 from Magic Realism: The Art of Weimar Germany at Tate Modern, London 30th July 2018 to 14th July 2019.#magicrealism #weimargermany #georgegrosz #albertbirkle #jeannemammen #sergiuspauser  #tate #tatemodern #figurativepainting #modernart #talkingaboutart #painter #painting #art

text: 이곳을 보기 위해서라도 꼭 다시 피렌체에 와야지 했었어요! 라우렌치아나 도서관입니다. 미켈란젤로가 설계했어요. 그리고 이곳을 보고 마크 로스코가 영감을 받아 포시즌 호텔 벽화를 그렸었죠.  도서관에 들어가자 마자 이게 로스코가 느꼈던 답답함이었구나. 창문이 있는데 없는 거 도망갈 수 있을 거 같은데 없는 것.로스코 채플도 이 도서관도 또 테이트 모던의 작품까지 만났으니 이제 조금 더 로스코를 느낄 수 있겠죠? 조금은 왜 어떤 사람들은 로스코 그림 보는게 힘들다고 하는지 알 거 같아요.예술가들은 참 대단해요. 내가 지나치는 일상이 그들 눈에 어떻게 보이는 걸까요?_#라우렌치아나도서관 #도슨트__#이탈리아 #여행중 #꽃슨트 #미켈란젤로도서관 #피렌체 #좋다 #여행스타그램 #마크로스코 #미켈란젤로 #미술스타그램 #예술스타그램 #미술여행 #예술여행 #인문학여행 #여행 #여행사진 #런던 #테이트모던 #london  #tatemodern #italy #firenze #LaurentianLibrary #markrothko #Michelangelo

text: ☄️Olafur ELIASSON - Stardust Particle (2014)💫.“Eliasson began making works that explored LIGHT and COLOUR while he was a student at the Royal Danish Academy of Arts in Copenhagen, and these have remained cornerstones of his practice, as both media and subject matter. [...] From 2003 onwards, he became more concerned with their PSYCHOLOGICAL and PHYSICAL effects – at its simplest, how light and colour can manipulate how one feels in a particular environment.” @tate .@studioolafureliasson @tatecollective .#olafureliasson #eliasson #stardustparticle #artinstallation #contemporaryart #tatemodern #inreallife #tatemodernmuseum #londonmuseum #timeoutlondon #artdailydose #artinlondon #artgallerylondon #icelandicart #danishart #lightart #geometricart

name: 2019-09-17 02.31.01 2134355805357230542_tatemodern.jpg
text: Liverpool Mountain is Swiss-artist Ugo Rondinone's first public artwork in the UK and the first of its kind in Europe. Inspired by naturally occurring Hoodoos (spires or pyramids of rock) and the art of meditative rock balancing, this 10-metre high sculpture stands within Mermaid Courtyard, outside Tate Liverpool on the Royal Albert Dock Liverpool. It consists of coloured rocks, stacked vertically which seem to defy gravity.Source: tate.org.ukHave a colourful start into the week!#tategallery #tatemodern #ugorondinone

name: 2019-09-17 03.43.56 2134392505584554168_tatemodern.jpg
text: CAI GUO-QIANGMr Ye Who Loves Dragon drawing made from #combustible materials on paper B 1957, #China Know for: installation, sculpture, painting and drawing ••••This extraordinary piece is a large rectangular drawing on paper by the Chinese artist Cai Guo-Qiang that was created from the residue left by the ignition of combustible materials. The composition consists of an undulating line of dense brown and black material of varying density and width. The line is burnt into the paper, and follows the route of the ignition fuse arranged prior to detonation. The #scorch #marks are dark at the centre of the line and fade to a lighter brown at its periphery.The drawing is the residue or documentation of a #performance that took place inside the Turbine Hall at #Tate Modern in London on 29 January 2003 and is the smaller of two drawings created in front of an audience during the event. Commemorating Chinese New Year, the event launched Tate & Egg Live, a season of live performance pieces.Cai Guo-Qiang currently lives and works in New York City and New Jersey.••••#fineart #sculpture #installation #painting #drawing #caiguoqiang #tatemodern #newyork #newjersey #egglive

text: EXPOSICIÓN EN EL MUSEO DE SAN JUAN DE LA MATAEl 19 de julio de 2019 se ha inaugurado una nueva  exposición con el título : EL FUEGO EN EL PRADOHomenaje al Museo del Prado en su Bicentenario Complementa y amplía la exposición anterior sobre el mismo tema pero con obras pertenecientes al Museo del Prado: Velázquez, Rubens, Goya, El Bosco, Cossiers,.....Y como plato fuerte:“Un cuadro viviente...”!!!!!! Santalla & StrartS y QuinSan han creado la Asociación de Museos Virtuales, cuyo fin es que todos los pueblos, independientemente de su población, puedan disponer de un museo de arte.El lema es: NINGÚN PUEBLO SIN MUSEO.EXHIBITION AT THE SAN JUAN DE LA MATA MUSEUMOn July 19, 2019 a new exhibition with the title was inaugurated:THE FIRE IN THE PRADOTribute to the Prado Museum in its BicentennialIt complements and extends the previous exhibition on the same subject but with works belonging to the Museo del Prado: Velázquez, Rubens, Goya, El Bosco, Cossiers, .....And as a main course:"A living painting ..." !!!!!! Santalla & StrartS and QuinSan have created the Association of Virtual Museums, whose goal is that all peoples, regardless of their population, can have an art museum.The motto is:NO PEOPLE WITHOUT MUSEUM.#museodelprado  #reinasofiamuseum #caixaforum #museothyssen #hermitagemuseum #whitneymuseum #centrepompidou  #nationalgallery  #moma #modernart #museedorsay #louvre #met  #britishmuseum  #tatemodern #guggenheim #nycart #brooklynmuseum #lacmamuseum #gemaldegalerie #artinstitutechicago #ufizzi  #louvreabudhabi #yaleartgallery #galleriaborghese #gettymuseum #sfmoma #nationalgalleryofart #altepinakothek #rijksmuseum

name: 2019-09-17 06.41.11 2134481719251978716_tatemodern.jpg
text: The ‘Sound & Silence’ is my favourite part of Takis exhibition currently being displayed at Tate Modern. The sculptures produce sounds ranging from simple notes to thunderous ensembles with power to hypnotise, shock, amaze, draw you in and transfer to another world-the mystical kind. These Signals sculptures were his first experiment with sound and in my humble opinion, extremely successful. Signals sculptures were formed with metal poles and coiling piano wires. They respond to surrounding air currents, generating delicate sounds, which in other words, these artworks have a life of their own as their sounds cannot be fully controlled. This is just a small portion of this amazing exhibition and each section deserves a separate post - definitely worth experiencing. Panasyiotis Vassilakis aka Takis, an #artist #activist #greatmind #inventor #forwardthinker...#tatemodern #londonexhibition #mustsee #artlondon #londonart #londonartscene #londonartgallery #takis #exhibition #sculptures #exhibitionart #modernart #modernartwork

name: 2019-09-17 07.36.53 2134509754609638877_tatemodern.jpg
text: What does it feel like to have limited visibility when you have to pass through a foggy, 39-metre tunnel? It’s pretty disconcerting and you really have to rely on your other human senses. Olifur Eliasson’s highly experimental work, ‘Din blinde passager’ (2010), basically lets you experience that. It was a little bit more for me... it was both an emotional and freeing experience. So much about feeling trapped and being blinded by circumstances, followed by the moments of epiphany that there are endless possibilities waiting at the end of the tunnel. That life is a journey that is full of unknowns and you will go through various highs and lows. To learn, to grow and to make it all worthwhile. Perhaps it was not meant to be interpreted that way, but it felt relatable back then. Who knows. #dinblindepassager #yourblindpassenger #olifureliasson #art #contemporaryart #inyourlife #tatemodern #london #instaart

name: 2019-09-17 15.57.36 2134761780730253628_tatemodern.jpg
text: MARY CASSATT: A MODERN WOMAN..“I hated conventional art. I began to live.”. .Mary Cassatt was a painter’s painter, capturing her subjects with open, fluid brushstrokes loaded with energy and life. Rising to prominence in 19th century Paris, style was as radical as content, as bold brushstrokes and dazzling colours captured the minutiae of ordinary life with the rapid eye of a true Impressionist. Yet as a female painter surrounded by men her world view was bound to be different from her male peers, providing a vital woman’s perspective on modern urban living. Though history has tended to sentimentalise her art, particularly her many portrayals of women and children (often referred to as ‘modern day Madonnas’) there are depths of psychoanalysis beneath their apparent contentment, acting as astute observations on the roles women and young girls were expected to play. Professor and theorist Griselda Pollock notes, “Recognising her novel and intensely formal explorations of … subjectivity … we can … appreciate the symbolist interest in psycho-social complexities (she) shared with modernist writers and thinkers.”..Little Girl in a Blue Armchair / Mary Cassatt / 1878...To read full article follow link in bio. name: 2019-09-17 16.48.43 2134787500982539226_tatemodern.jpg
text: Spårvagnen (c.1943).🎨 Painted by Olle Olsson.Born: 12 July 1904, Hagalund, Solna, Sweden.Died: 13 June 1972, Hagalund, Solna, Sweden..🖼 Oil on canvas 85 x 90 cm..📝 Olle Olsson-Hagalund is one of Sweden's most appreciated naive artists during the twentieth century. The village Hagalund, Olle Olsson's main source of inspiration, is gone. However his own house and three others still stand which.Olle Olsson Hagalund's naive dreamlike imagery lost some of its popularity during the 60' and 70'. Progressive artistic trends which often involved some political statement lead the art community in Sweden during these two decades. Today however we have rediscovered how timeless the artist was in expressing a blend of dramatic humour with quiet melancholy in a simple lifestyle. Perhaps this technocratic society we live in needs now more than ever his sensitive and loving relationship to relics from the past and his talent for narrative art. As an artist he will always invigorate us with his vibrant array of colours and the intrinsic value of his artistic talents.As a child Olle Olsson was a loner. He often wandered by himself contemplating - observing his surroundings - and drawing. After school, Olle sought employmet at The National Railway Company. He was later dismissed when the company introduced a rationalization program and with small savings in his pocket he registered at the Carl Wilhelmssons Painting School. He spent only a short time at the school. Olle Olsson felt uneasy in the company of colourfull and expressive painters. He began to doubt his competence and was not very disappointed when lack of money forced him to leave. During the following years, Olle Olssonhad long periods of unemployment. He painted in secrecy and did not show his art to anyone.In 1943 the PUB department store organized a competition for young painters. Olle Olsson sent in six paintings of which all were accepted.The critics praised his colouristic talent and ability to bring to life the shabby suburbs in Hagalund.The artist's private life was spent quietly in Hagalund with his wife Maja, whom he married in 1937, and his daughter Lena who was born in 1950....

name: 2019-09-17 17.44.55 2134815792336083705_tatemodern.jpg
text: #Gasworks25 #GasworksArchive Throughout 2019 Gasworks celebrates 25 years of supporting artists. Over the course of the year we will be digging into our archive to highlight our unique, long-standing relationship with artists. This week we are highlighting South African artist Kemang Wa Lehulere, whose first solo UK exhibition ‘Sincerely yours,’ ran from 24 Sep – 8 Nov 2015. The exhibition took as its starting point the South African intellectual Sol Plaatje’s journeys to England in the early twentieth century to petition against the 1913 Natives Land Act, which helped lay the groundwork for apartheid. Including chalk-on-blackboard drawings, wall etchings and soil and grass sculptures, the exhibition staged a speculative encounter between Plaatje’s past and its interpretation by the artist in the present, weaving and unravelling the relationships between personal and collective histories, amnesia and the archive. You can read more on our online archive – link in bio. To accompany the exhibition Kemang Wa Lehulere also produced an exclusive #limitededition print which can be purchased from our online shop. Kemang Wa Lehulere’s installation ‘I cut my skin to liberate the splinter’ is currently on display in The Tanks at #TateModern until 6th October. @tate @stevenson_sa @kemangwalehulere #KemangWaLehulere #gasworkslondon

text: Serene and beautiful this art is not!.Reveling in the depraved, the carnal and the misogynistic, the art of the Weimar Republic is often ugly and perhaps over-rated. text: Aujourd'hui je veux vous présenter l'oeuvre puissante d'une artiste brésilienne : Adriana Varejão. 🤩Elle a des oeuvres dans les plus grands musées d'art contemporain au monde : Moma, Guggenheim, Tate... 👏👏👏Elle utilise les "azuleijos" portugais pour dialoguer avec le passé colonial brésilien et elle questionne ce rapport fait parfois de souffrances et de brutalité. On découvre parfois la "chair" derrière ces magnifiques et élégants azuleijos. C'est un travail qui ne laisse pas indéférent et que j'ai pu revoir à Inhotim cet été. 😍Une oeuvre majeure !.......#cristinacordula #adrianavarejao #inhotim #moma #tatemodern #guggenheim #artbrésilien #artcontemporain #fondationcartier

text: Tuesday Traveling--I'm in London and Oxford, so this post will be the only "extra" this week. I've been enjoying galleries on this trip and am including a few of my favorite encounters here. I often think of the distinction between making and appreciating art as being similar to playing and watching sports. You certainly don't have to be a professional to be an artist or to take pleasure in playing a sport, but doing does make you appreciate the professionals more. Though I'm hardly a peer or on par with these artists, I do experience a strange fellow-feeing when I look at their work...#museumart #britishmuseum #nationalgallery #nottinghill #tatemodern #artinferioritycomplex #abstractart #intuitiveart #visualart #visualartist #gesturalabstraction #brokeartist

name: 2019-09-18 01.13.40 2135041650959691783_tatemodern.jpg
text: Сегодня мы были в новом крыле британской галереи современного искусства Tate - Blavatnick Building.  Блаватник пожертвовал крупную сумму, потому его именем новое крыло и назвали. Вообще он в Британии во многие проекты вложился: в прошлом году купил старейший театр в Вест-Энде Royal Haymarket, профинансировал новый вестибюль в музее Виктории и Альберта, а в Оксфордском университете ещё и  бизнес-школа имени Блаватника открылась.Но сейчас, конечно, не о нем - а о самом пространстве. Вот бы здесь снимать!, - думала я, глядя на все эти неповторяющиеся залы и коридоры. Очень причудливо падает свет, бетон, кирпич, то что надо для фэшн. Строительство этого крыла началось в 2009 году по проекту бюро Herzog & de Meuron Architekten на месте бывшей электростанции. По словам самого архитектора Жака Херцога, форма здания напоминает «пирамиду в стадии распада». Здесь выставлено искусство с 1960-х годов до наших дней.#будниредактора #архитектура #современноеискусство #лондон #тейтмодерн #тейт #путешествие #tategallery #tatemodern #london #architecture #architecturelovers #citylife #interiordesign

name: 2019-09-18 02.25.16 2135077687396711075_tatemodern.jpg
text: A little climate victory: London’s River Thames was so polluted in the 1960’s that it was declared biologically dead. This had been caused by pollution from industry since the Industrial Revolution, including waste from the coal and oil-fired Bankside Power Station (1952-1981) which would later become the Tate Modern. As my contribution to the opening of a group exhibition at the art museum in 2015, I proposed to catch and release something from the river to celebrate its successful rehabilitation over the last decades. Conservationists have counted more than 125 species of fish in the river since positive measures were taken to clean it up. My son Theriodopiolus, godson Lucas and his sister Margot assisted me in the ambitious fishing plan and it was Margot’s line which caught the eel. ⚡️If the Thames can be fixed, then surely we stand a chance to do the same with other rivers and our oceans?(Black and white image of Bankside Power Station was sourced from the internet, photographer and date unknown)#globalclimatestrike#climateaction#extinctionrebellionlondon #extinctionrebellion#tatemodern

text: FS COLOR SERIES: REED INSPIRED BY W.R. SICKERT'S SILVERY BLUE ....Moody, sombre and filled with suspense, the silvery blue tone in REED linen was entrancing for British painter Walter Richard Sickert, allowing him to convey scenes lit by a soft, diffused light. From the murky waters and metallic skies of Venice to delicate, intimate interiors, Sickert conveyed a spectrum of subjects with this colour throughout his career, filling his work with a quiet, ghostly sense of anticipation. He was particularly fascinated with the ways paintings, through the careful depiction of colour and light, could suddenly lift everyday scenes into the realms of the mystical and otherworldly, observing, “one day something happens, the touches seem to ‘take’, the deaf canvas listens, your words flow and you have done something.”...To read full article please follow link in bio. 💫.....#fabricsstorecom #jmwturner #impressionism #tatemodern #textiledesign #embroidery #textile #craft #arthistory #moderncraftsman #postimpressionism #painting #landscapepainting #moderncraft #artist #art #moma #maker #makersgonnamake #isew #memade #ethicalfashion #textile #slowfashion #modernweaving #embroidery #embroideryart #weaving

name: 2019-09-18 04.20.09 2135135515381255873_tatemodern.jpg
text: 💡GLENN LIGON 💡▪️America | 2008 | @rubellcollection▪️This semester I’m taking a class about the groundbreaking exhibition “30 Americans,” which presents work by many of the world’s most influential black artists. I am so excited about this class because we will help curate the show when it moves to the Barnes Foundation in late October. I have to write about a few artworks each week, so I’ve decided to pare down my responses and share them with you guys too.▪️Glenn Ligon is known for using language to explore themes of race, sexuality, and identity. Ligon employs text from important authors like James Baldwin and Zora Neale Hurston, repeating famous lines in neon and writing out entire passages in charcoal. So it is interesting that his most recognizable — and perhaps most compelling — work consists of a single word: America. What makes this artwork special is its immediacy and accessibly (two things that are not always the case with Ligon). The most effective aspect of this artwork, though, is its ambiguity. Anyone can approach the work and draw their own unique conclusions about its meaning. Some may see the work and feel a sense of national pride, while others may read it as a symbol of oppression. Hence, Ligon is exposing the dichotomies embedded in our American system, with a particular focus on race and class. The work makes me question how and why my reaction might differ from that of a black woman, or an undocumented immigrant. How does my experience — my privilege as a white male — define my understanding of America? As I think about this work, I can’t help but liken it to Jasper Johns’s Flag paintings form the mid-1950s. Johns similarly explored America’s social differences in the midst of the Civil Rights Movement and the Cold War. Perhaps fittingly, Ligon’s work revisited these important questions as we entered a new period of social and economic turmoil in 2008.▪️(If some of this looks familiar, thats because I recycled some thoughts from the very similar Jasper Johns painting I posted last week)

name: 2019-09-18 05.09.26 2135160314470248681_tatemodern.jpg
text: ❣️...The Spiritual Form of Nelson Guiding Leviathan (c.1805-9) by William Blake ..One of my fav finds from this exhibition! Love how this particular painting was displayed to restore its vibrant colours. ...._____________________________....Blake showed this painting in his 1809 exhibition. It was exhibited alongside The Spiritual Form of Pitt Guiding Behemoth. He provided a long commentary on his ‘spiritual forms’ of both Pitt and Nelson. The recently-deceased Prime Minster William Pitt and naval hero Admiral Nelson had both led Britain in the war against France. Blake shows these national figures guiding biblical monsters bringing chaos and destruction to the world. The symbolism used is complex. In the picture of Nelson ‘The Nations of the Earth’ are shown as contorted figures enveloped by the serpent. A figure of colour in chains lies collapsed at the bottom. He appears to be freed of the serpent’s coils, perhaps suggesting that such destruction could also lead to new freedoms and spiritual rebirth. ... .......................__

name: 2019-09-18 05.32.16 2135171813634988294_tatemodern.jpg
text: Glacial art by Olafur Eliasson, until January 5, 2020 at the Tate Modern, London. Eliasson often uses glacial ice in his work. Sometimes, the ice is intended as a call for action against the climate emergency. Warmer climates have caused the Greenland ice sheet to lose around 200–300 billion tonnes of glacial ice each year, a rate that is expected to increase dramatically. Ice Watch, which was staged in front of Tate Modern in 2018, is an installation of ice blocks fished from the water off the coast of Greenland. It offered a direct and tangible experience of the reality of melting Arctic ice.Other works are a more abstract reference to the changing environment. In Glacial currents 2018, chunks of glacial ice were placed on top of washes of coloured pigment. This created swells and fades of colour as they melted onto the paper beneath.•••@olafur_eliasson @tate #tatemodern #glacialart #environmentalart #retrospective #unmissable #art #london

text: ‘Verb 2 Sense, Sense’ (‘Colours’ series, 2018)‘COLOURS’ series is a comment on NUANCES of the language, AS WELL AS the nuance of ‘colours’...language can be equally USEFUL=USELESS...and I still, (steal) find it FUNDAMENTAL even if we all borrow the words we speak. ‘COLOURS’ is one of my comments on ‘THE ABSOLUTE POSSIBILITY OF DIS UNDERSTANDING’ which is not about ‘Misunderstanding’ it is about being understood in ways we do not really mean or maybe we do mean, ITS ABOUT THE CHANCE OF PLAYING finite and infinite GAMES. @artspace Reyzorro#contemporaryart#reyzorro @artspace #whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #NewMediaArt #fashion #art#tategallery

text: Verb2: Lie,Lay (Down) with Me -S.N.F.S.’(Sample Not 4 sale) 14’x8’ feet - 4.26x 2.40m. B side. Combine paintings, painted on both sides in case you want to ‘turn it around’. Rey UK 1999. Those pieces were stolen from my studio  at Metropolitan Wharf, Wapping, 6th floor, no lift...while I was in Brazil for 6 months helping my mom with cancer, who died. This/those people stole EVERYTHING from my studio, ALL my working tools that I’ve worked for 1 year from 6 in the morning on my local DIY shop (Tower DIY) to be able to buy staff price, paint, wood and stole my best clothes & shoes! How evil is that???? Whoever you are, you are cursed for life mate by me my mom and all my friends who saw how hard I worked preparing my biggest show here at Concord Sylvania Gallery in High Holborn Covent Garden. I spent 7 years without wanting to ever paint again. Obviously it was someone that new they existed and prepared a truck coz they were hudge and many! But I’m back trusty ready to rock’n roll.#contemporaryart#reyzorro @artspace #whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #NewMediaArt #fashion #artistsoninstagram #saatchigallery

text: Join spoken word artist and writer #IsaiahHull reading from #Nosebleeds, his debut poetry collectionIsaiah Hull’s Nosebleeds is a visceral and raw collection showcasing a voice far older than the poet’s young years. Hull’s writing is soul-searching and down to earth, written to be performed and yet transferring onto the page with remarkable clarity and ease. Nosebleeds is an exploration of self-expression, traversing emotion and form.Isaiah will read from his work, followed by a Q & A and book signing.#Nosebleeds is published by #wreckingballpress BiographyIsaiah Hull is one of the Roundhouse/Radio 1 Extra finalists in 2015 at the age of 18, having participated in Wordcup, a national youth slam run by @applesandsnakes . Hull is inspired by Saul Williams, Philip Larkin and classical Greek tragedies. He is a member of the young writers collective, #youngidentity Young Identity, which was formed in Moss Side to encourage young adults and teenagers to express themselves through poetry. He has supported #Kate Tempest, Lemn Sissay and #Skepta at major events for the #BBC and his #tedxtalks Unexplained Virtue of Ignorance has over 5000 views.#spokenwordpoetry #poetrycommunity #poetrycommunity #tatemodern #tategallery #TerraceshopBanksideLondon SE1 9TGPlan your visitDATE & TIME25 October 2019 at 19.00–20.00PRICINGFREE with ticketTickets available from 5pm on the day from the Level 0 ticket desk. text: მონოლოგი:შენი აზრით,დროს რა მოაქვს?მიდის,მიდის,არ ჩერდება ან საუკუნესავით იწელება.ფიქრები მაშინ მანებებენ თავს,როცა გონება ბოლომდე ითიშება,მანამდე კი მარწუხებივით მიჭერენ და ცდილობენ ტკივილის სიალოვნება არ მომაკლონ.რა ხდება,როცა ყველა გაქარვებული სევდა ესთად შემოგაწვება?ირგვლივ სრული ქაოსია,თუმცა შენ მაინც იცი სად არის დასაწყისი,მაგრამ დასასრულს ვერ ხედავ,ბოლო ამ ყველაფრის იმდენად შორსაა,რომ სიბნელეში ერთ მოკიაფე პატარა ვარსკვლავსაც კი ვერ შეამჩნევ.თითქოს ნათელი შეცვლის არსებულს,თითქოს გამოასწორებს ყვრლაფერს,თითქოს წონასწორობას მოიტანს,ვინ იცის?!გიგრძვნია მარტოობა ისე ცხადად,რომ ყველაზე უსუსურად წარმოგედგინა თავი?სიტყვები იწერება და ნაბიჯები ვერ იდგმევა,სიტყვები იწერება და ბოლომდე ვერ ამბობენ სათქმელს,სიტყვები,რომლებიც დარდს გამოსჭვივიან.მე პირადად ვერაფერს ვუხერხებ ამ შეგრძნებებს,დროს მიააქვს და მოაქვს,მაგრამ არ აქრობს,ისინი უსასრულოდ ცოცხლობენ და ჩნდებიან,ყველა ჩემნაირ ადამიათან მაშინვე,როცა იგრძნობენ ჩვენს სიმარტოვეს.სულისშემხუთავი მდგომარეობას ვერ ცვლის დრო,აჩერებს,მაგრამ არა სამუდამოდ...............#blackwhite, #black, #white, #bnw, #bnw_captures, #bnw_life, #bnw_society, #blackandwhitephotography, #bnw_planet, #bnw_city, #bnw_globe, #Bw_crew #Photograph #Bnw_society #Photographer #Blacknwhite #Blacknwhite_perfection #Instablackandwhite #bw #Insta_bw #bnw_lumeilo #vintagephotography #photomanipulation #scacco_matto_ #tatemodern #architecturephotography #architecture

name: 2019-09-18 16.26.56 2135501316839806148_tatemodern.jpg
text: ‘Armstrong’ , tribute to Armstrong mixed media, 6x4’ feet, 1.82x1.21meters. Rey UK 1999. Those pieces were stolen from my studio  at Metropolitan Wharf, Wapping, 6th floor, no lift...while I was in Brazil for 6 months helping my mom with cancer, who died. This/those people stole EVERYTHING from my studio, ALL my working tools that I’ve worked for 1 year from 6 in the morning on my local DIY shop (Tower DIY) to be able to buy staff price, paint, wood and stole my best clothes & shoes! How evil is that???? Whoever you are, you are cursed for life mate by me my mom and all my friends who saw how hard I worked preparing my biggest show here at Concord Sylvania Gallery in High Holborn Covent Garden. I spent 7 years without wanting to ever paint again. Obviously it was someone that new they existed and prepared a truck coz they were hudge and many! But I’m back trusty ready to rock’n roll.#contemporaryart#reyzorro @artspace #whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #NewMediaArt #fashion #artistsoninstagram #saatchigallery

text: 스쳐가 버린 휴가가 무척이나 그리워져 돌아본 27일 런던 일정.이날은 맘마미아 데이시트 티켓을 사기 위해 오전에 가고 싶었던 여러 군데를 도장찍듯 지나갈 수밖에 없었다. 그 와중에도 런던의 세인트 제임스 파크는 소위 '숲세권'이 왜 생겨났는지 직관적으로 깨닫게 만든다. 아침 8시 출근 시간이 한창인데도 돗자리도 없이 햇볕 좋은 곳에 누워 일광욕을 즐기는 사람들을 보면 참 행복이 느껴진다.버킹엄 궁전은 여는 시간도 애매하고, 제대로 보려면 돈을 내야 한다기에 그냥 밖에서 외관만 보고 지나갔다.데이시트로 볼 뮤지컬은 알라딘과 라이언킹, 맘마미아 중 하나로 고민했다. 하지만 라이언킹 데이시트는 새벽 6시부터 줄을 서야 한다는 글을 봤고, 알라딘도 크게 다르지 않을 거라는 생각이 들어 그냥 맘마미아를 선택했다. 그 맘마미아 마저도 데이시트 구매 시간보다 1시간 15분 일찍 왔는데 이미 내 앞에 13명의 사람이 있었으니 과연 뮤지컬은 런던의 명물이다. 특이한 점으로는 내 앞의 13명 중 절반 이상이 한국인이었고, 그들 모두 여성이었으며, 초면인 듯 싶었지만 서로 한국어로 여행의 소회를 나누고 있었다는 걸 꼽을 수 있겠다. 10시가 다 돼서는 50대 가량의 중년 한국 커플 두 쌍이 와 티켓을 살 수 있을지 불안해 해, 그 모습을 보고 다음에는 런던에서만 볼 수 있는 생소한 작품을 골라야지 다짐했던 게 기억난다.표를 사고 나서 바로 테이트 브리튼을 갔다. 과연 '브리튼'이라는 단어가 들어갈 만한 작품 선이다. 한 3년 전부터 좋아하던 작가 프란시스 베이컨의 작품을 보고 소름이 끼쳤고, 윌리엄 터너로 뒤덮인 어마어마한 공간을 보고 천국이 있다면 여길까 싶었다. 테이트 브리튼에는 영국 현대미술가들의 작품도 많아 테이트 모던으로 이동하기 전 훌륭한 워밍업이 됐다.테이트 모던으로는 배를 타고 갔다. 템즈 강은 참 지저분하다. 한 치 앞이 안 보이는 똥물이나 다름 없다. 그 와중에 테이트 사원증(?)을 목에 걸고 배를 타는 직원 분을 보고 스웩이 남다르다 느꼈다.첫 날에 이어 두 번째로 방문한 테이트 모던은 다시 한 번 그 방대함에 감탄했다. 무료 전시를 쭉 훑어보는 것만으로도 3시간은 그냥 지나갔다. 특별전으로 열린 올라퍼 엘리아슨 전시를 보려 했으나 이미 티켓 구매 시간을 넘겨서 그냥 말았다. 스토어에서 관련 도록을 보고 볼 껄 그랬다는 아쉬움이 들었지만 테이트 브리튼과 모던을 거치며 들어온 작품 정보의 양이 너무 많았던 터라 이것만으로도 충분하다 싶었다.맘마미아가 열리는 노벨로 극장에 도착하니 한 시간이나 떠 근처에 있는 코벤트 가든 시장에 갔다. 시장에 들어거면서부터 볼 수 있는 꽃들이 참 예뻤다. 시장 중심에는 지하를 볼 수 있는 상점 단지가 있는데, 밑에서 콰르텟 일당이 즉흥연주를 벌여 귀가 호강이었다. 그 일당은 자신들의 음반을 팔며 모객행위를 했는데, 15분 동안 아무도 사지 않는 처지가 조금 안쓰러웠다. 이제와 돌이켜보면 나라도 살 껄 그랬다 싶다.이런 여정 끝에 본 맘마미아는 너무 좋았다. 숙소로 돌아와서 굳이 영화 맘마미아 OST를 찾아 들을 정도로 정서적 여운이 컸다. 다만 너무 늦게 끝나 이 날 여행을 돌아보는 글을 쓸 수 없었고, 아이러니하게도 회사에 있는 지금 노벨로 극장에서 느꼈던 감정이 그리워져 기어이 지난 8월 27일을 복기했다.아... 다시 가고 싶다 런던... 너무나도 다시 가고 싶다 흑흑.#saintjamesparklondon#세인트제임스파크런던 #buckinghampalace #버킹엄궁전 #tatebritain #테이트브리튼 #thamesrivercruise #템즈강유람선 #tatemodern #테이트모던 #coventgardenmarket #코벤트가든마켓 #novellotheatre #mammamia #노벨로극장 #맘마미아

text: Going back to work hit me hard and I needed a break from some non vital yet time consuming activities, like social network. 😂 But now I'm back and ready to post the last pictures of the trip @lukehousegods and I did in the UK this summerThis was DAY 7: LodonSince it was Saturday we went straight to Portobello, I love that market, place for both bargain and poor choices 😂. We wandered around Notting Hill and than had a nice good walk in the park, Kensington Gardens first, then Hide Park with a quick stop at the Serpentine Gallery.Then we decided to abandon the quiet of the park and dive into the liveliness of the South Bank. To my surprise, the Tate Modern was opened till late (again, Saturday) so we had the chance to see some of the exhibitions. After a late dinner at the Shakespeare Globe restaurant we decided it was time to get some rest so we crossed the Millennium Bridge and went straight to St Paul's Cathedral to catch a train back to the hotel. #london #visitlondon #travelintheuk #traveller #worldtraveller #history #culture #architecture #art #nature #instalondon #instauk #iglondon #igerslondon #portobelloroad #portobellomarket #nottinghill #kensington #kensingtongardens #hydepark #theserpentinegallery #southbank #londoneye #shakespeareglobe #tatemodern #millenniumbridge #stpaul #instagrammer #instamoment #toptag

name: 2019-09-18 18.40.53 2135568728524493389_tatemodern.jpg
text: The massacres of Sabra and Shatila, in Beirut, began on the 16th of September, 1982, and lasted until the early morning of the 18th. Somewhere up to 3,000 non-combatant men, women, and children were murdered by Lebanese Catholic militia. The painting here is the work of artist Dia Azzawi, a response to the massacre in its immediate aftermath. It hangs in London; the photo, of course, and the commentary following are mine. #TateModern #DiaAzzawi #Art #painting #poetry #poems #photography #Lebanon

name: 2019-09-18 18.58.12 2135577452465085394_tatemodern.jpg
text: 2020年春夏ロンドンコレ2日目のハイライト　「トーガ」や新生「ポーツ1961」など﻿﻿　ロンドンコレ2日目の9月14日は、一般公開の“パブリックショー”が公式スケジュール内で開催され、多くの一般客もファッション・ウイークを楽しんだ。20ブランドから厳選3ブランドをレポートする。﻿﻿ポーツ1961（PORTS 1961）﻿DESIGNER／カール・テンプラー﻿﻿　クリエイティブなプロ集団による新生「ポーツ1961」のデビューコレクションが、美術館のテート・モダンでベールを脱いだ。「サカイ（SACAI）」のショースタイリストとしても知られるカール・テンプラー（Karl Templer）をアーティスティック・ディレクターに起用し、「ディオール（DIOR）」から「ザラ（ZARA）」までをクライアントに持つアートディレクターのファビアン・バロン（Fabien Baron）らから知恵を集めて新たなブランド像を発信する。﻿﻿今季はブランドの創業者である日系カナダ人実業家、ルーク・タナベが日本産シルクを輸入して世界へ広め、国際的な背景を持って60年代の女性たちに洋服を提案していったルーツをもとに、文化の融合をコラージュで表現した。アクセサリー提案が豊作で、アニマル柄をコラージュしたストラップサンダルをはじめ、ミニショルダーバッグ、大振りのピアスやネックレスなどが登場した。これらのアクセサリーや、フィッシュネットのセカンドスキントップスなどの装飾性の高いアイテムは、スタイリストのテンプラーならではのアイデアだ。﻿﻿その他、「トーガ」と「モリー ゴダード」のコレクション・レポートはストーリーまたはプロフィールのリンクこら🔗﻿﻿PHOTOS : GIOVANNI GIANNONI / WWD (c) FAIRCHILD PUBLISHING, LLC﻿﻿#PORTS1961 #KarlTempler #FabienBaron #LFW #tatemodern

name: 2019-09-18 19.00.25 2135578566692056225_tatemodern.jpg
text: We love London and we love London’s museums and galleries even more. This is the view from the Tate Modern members bar on a glorious Autumn evening. Last week @frieze_magazine announced that The Tate Modern has appointed four new curators specializing in African, Middle Eastern and South Asian art. Nabila Abdel Nabi, who moves from The Power Plant, Toronto, will focus on art from the Middle East and North Africa. Curator, critic, art historian and frieze contributing editor Osei Bonsu will work on developing representation of African art in Tate’s collection and public programme. Dr Devika Singh, a specialist in modern and contemporary art and architecture in South Asia, as well as a regular contributor to frieze, will lead on curating art from that region. And Valentina Ravaglia, previously assistant curator at Tate Modern, will be working on the collection display programme. ‘These posts will further Tate’s commitment to rethinking the history of modern and contemporary art from a less Western-centric vantage point,’ reads the press release. Frances Morris, director of Tate.•#tatemodern #tate #southasianart #middleeasternart #africanart #asianart #curator #museum #artmuseum #collection #exhibition #london #londonartscene #londonartmuseum #studyasianart #postgraduate #postgraduatediplomainasianart

text: Damien Hirst “I love going around aquariums;(…) glass becomes something that holds you back and lets you in at the same time (….) It’s probably my favourite material, glass. And water.(…) Glass in water is amazing; glass disappears if you put it in water.”Remembering Hirst’s iconic retrospective at the @tate in 2012. The exhibition featured over 70 of Hirst's works spanning three decades of his career and occupying 14 whole rooms ! The last two images were taken at @ordovasgallery where Hirst’s formaldehyde shark ‘ Heaven, 2008- 2009’ was exhibited as part of the exhibition ‘The Big Blue’ in 2015.#tatemodern #damienhirst #exhibition #retrospective #ordovasgallery #thebigblue #formaldehyde

text: Serene and beautiful this art is not!.Reveling in the depraved, the carnal and the misogynistic, the art of the Weimar Republic is often ugly and perhaps over-rated. text: 유럽 미술관 탐방기 2영국 런던 테이트 모던(Tate Modern Collection)현대 미술의 중심을 뉴욕에서 런던으로 옮겨왔다는 평가를 받는 테이트 모던은 21세기 최고의 현대미술관이라 불리기도 한다. 20세기 이후의 작품들 위주로 회화부터 설치 미술까지 여러 분야의 현대 미술의 흐름과 현재 가장 핫한 작가들의 작품까지 감상할수 있었다. 인지도가 높고 소장가치가 높은 작품들을 주로 전시하기 때문에 유명한 작품들이 많다. 작품을 감상하며 걷다보면 미술관 유리창 너머로 보이는 해지는 템즈강..런던 뽕에 취한다😂🔫 사실상 테이트 모던때문에 런던을 오기로 결심했다고 해도 과언이 아닌데 버킷리스트를 하나 지운 것 같아서 기분이 묘했다. ...#런던여행 #테이트모던 #london #tatemodern #tatemodernmuseum

name: 2019-09-18 23.12.12 2135705295917964485_tatemodern.jpg
text: ART. we are art, you know why, coz our God has created us! We are His creations, we are His “masterpiece” even though we may not feel it! We have been made in His image, in His likeness. We are His and He is ours y’all! Why don’t we ever appreciate our art piece? In who we are? About how we have been made? We have been made fearfully and wonderfully! We are a piece of art, why is it so hard for us to believe in that!? We each have been created with a purpose, how cool is that?! Each and everyone of us have been known by our Creator even before we were formed in our mothers’ womb! We are His work of art, should we not respect and rejoice in our God!? So, may you remember today that God loves you for just the way you are! From your eye colour and your height to your shoe size! He loves’em all! Take joy in His creation and not in how you perceive yourself!

name: 2019-09-19 00.37.38 2135748293907551553_tatemodern.jpg
text: Ned Osborne on 'Grey Tick', Zennor Hill, Cornwall..🎨 Painted by Sir Alfred James Munnings.Born: 8 October 1878, Mendham, Suffolk, England.Died: 17 July 1959, Dedham, Essex, England. (aged 80).🖼 Oil on canvas 63,5 x 76,2 cm..📝 Showing some early talent, Munnings was apprenticed to a firm of lithographers, Page Brothers in Norwich for six years, studying at Norwich School of Art in the evening.He had some success locally and showed two paintings at the Royal Academy in 1899. In the same year he returned to set up his studio in Mendham, and in an accident lost the sight in one eye.In his early years he supplemented his income by designing posters at which, with is consummate draughtsmanship he excelled. He studied briefly in Paris between 1902 and 1903.Munnings drew his subject matter from the East Anglian landscape and rural society. A horse fair of 1901 showed an early interest in horses while fairgrounds and rural occupations provided the artist with considerable subject matter.1910 saw Munnings visit Lamorna in Cornwall where he met Laura and Harold Knight, lifelong friends, and where he stayed between 1911 and 1916.In 1913 he held his first one-man show at the Leicester Galleries, where Laura Knight showed.In 1918 Munnings was appointed as a war artist with the Canadian Cavalry Brigade, producing an important body of work for the Canadian Government.Munnings settled in Dedham in 1918, marrying Violet in 1920. He was elected Royal Academician in 1925.In 1944 Munnings was knighted and elected President of the Royal Academy between 1944 and 1949. In this latter role he famously made known his utter contempt for ‘Modern Art’. Munnings was a prolific artist and a consummate draughtsman, whose work as a war artist raised his profile and reputation.Best known for his equestrian works, portraits and racing works, Munnings range was enormous. He excelled in landscape and scenes of rural life, recording a way of life that was coming to an end.His works can be found in museums in: Birmingham; Liverpool; London, Tate Gallery; Norwich; Preston; USA, Yale University; Brisbane and Melbourne..(Fig 2, 3, 4: Details)...

text: Once we went to Noma in CPH and there was a delicious course of woodland carpet moss that had been brined and then dipped and covered in white chocolate.  You were meant to eat it all in its entirety. The brining process made it not poisonous thankfully, and the white chocolate made it delectable.  This wall on the other hand looked the same but it wasn't. It's at the Tate Modern, you can touch it, but you can't eat it. Fun.⁠->⁠Top to bottom Colour card:⁠-⁠Almond Drink - Rot - Greige - Slip - Lactoderm⁠⁠⁠⁠⁠#color #colour #rainbow #colourful #spectrum #pantone #gradient #colourislife #colouralchemy #coloralchemy #colourpalette #colorpalette #Colourspectrum  #OlafurEliasson #TateModern #MossWall #EdibleMoss #TouchIt #Youcantouchitifyouwant #BouncyWall #Tactile #ContemporaryArt #InstallationArt #LondonLife ⁠⁠⁠July17th, 2019. text: ‘Verb 2 You, You’ (‘Colours’ series, 2018)‘COLOURS’ series is a comment on NUANCES of the language, AS WELL AS the nuance of ‘colours’...language can be equally USEFUL=USELESS...and I still, (steal) find it FUNDAMENTAL even if we all borrow the words we speak. ‘COLOURS’ is one of my comments on ‘THE ABSOLUTE POSSIBILITY OF DIS UNDERSTANDING’ which is not about ‘Misunderstanding’ it is about being understood in ways we do not really mean or maybe we do mean, ITS ABOUT THE CHANCE OF PLAYING finite and infinite GAMES. @artspace Reyzorro#contemporaryart#reyzorro @artspace #whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #NewMediaArt #fashion #art#tategallery

name: 2019-09-19 01.44.13 2135781804359302866_tatemodern.jpg
text: Andy Warhol’s “Red Elvis,” 1962, in the Jed Johnson-designed home of collector and horseman Peter Brant. Since the early 1970s, Brant and his wives, first Sandy and later Stephanie Seymour, have built major holdings of their favorite artists: Andy Warhol, Jean-Michel Basquiat, Francesco Clemente and Jeff Koons. Works from the collection can be seen at the @brantfoundation in Greenwich, Connecticut and on the Lower East Side (formerly the studio of artist Walter de Maria). Brant is also known as a horse breeder (his horses won the Kentucky Derby in 1984 and 1995) and a player at @greenwichpoloclub and the @bridgehamptonpolo . His Warhols have been exhibited extensively, representing a significant portion of retrospectives at the @tate , #hamburgerbahnhof and recently at the @whitneymuseum . #livingwithart #artinthehome #jedjohnson #andywarhol #warhol #brantfoundation #thebrantfoundation #brantfoundationartstudycenter #jeanmichelbasquiat #jeffkoons #francescoclemente #whitneymuseum #tatemodern

text: Aquifer VII is from a series of monumental oils by contemporary artist Martyn Jones, that are expressions of the value he places on colour.Jones’ works of art have been compared with the work of Spanish Catalan Surrealist artist Joan Miró. Miró expressed contempt for conventional painting methods as a way of supporting bourgeois society, and famously declared an “assassination of painting” in favour of upsetting the visual elements of established painting.DIMENSIONS: (unframed) 78.74 x 78.74 in./ 200.0 x 200.0 cmSIGNATURE: SignedMEDIUM: Oil on canvasCatalogue No: 4766#fineart #martynjones #welshartist #contemporaryart #modernpainting #contemporaryartist #abstract #painting #abstractpainting #art #painter #tatemodern #colourfulart #curator #artdealer #artcollection #fineartcollection #welshart #originalfineart #originalart #abstraction #sanfrancisco #welshcontemporaryart #artforsale #exhibitor #martynjones #artgallery #abstract #abstractpainter #artcollector

text: GET ON YA BIKE!! 🚴 Had a great afternoon today cycling around London and seeing all the sites this lovely city has to offer so I thought I would do a post about it. Cycling doubles up as transport which makes it really easy to fit exercise into your weekly routine. Brisk cycling is a very effective way of burning calories so it is a great tool for controlling your weight . It is also low impact which means it is great for those suffering with bad joints and is softer on your joints than other high impact aerobic exercises.Cycling improves cardiovascular health and function, muscular strength and tone, bone mass density and posture aswell as mental well being and stress management. Another benefit I have always found with cycling is that it offers accessibility and a fresh perspective which allows you to discover new places and routes in your city the opportunity and the excuse to get out and see them! #london #londonisopen #cycling #cyclingphoto @britishcycling #buckinghampalace #trafalgarsquare #nationalgallery #tatemodern #unitedkingdom #personaltrainer #fitness #workout #fitnessmotivation #fit #motivation #training #fitfam #personaltraining #health #coach #lifestyle #exercise #gymmotivation #weightloss #nutrition #cardio #healthy #healthylifestyle #londoner #cyclinglife

text: ‘PRAGMA’ old Gold (TREE OF LOVE Rug series) based on real ‘Tree of Life’ Persian rugs, REY UK 2019Follow Amazing Artist @reyzorroPragma love in the BiblePragma is a kind of practical love founded on reason or duty and one's longer-term interests. Sexual attraction takes a back seat in favour of personal qualities and compatibilities shared goals and making it work. In the days of arranged marriages, pragma must have been very common.Tree of life rugs, also known as Tree rugs earn distinction as a representation of one of the most timeless religious symbols of human life, its use preceding Christianity and Islam. Ancient cultures throughout Europe and Asia view the tree of life as a link between man and heaven. Often, in Oriental rug producing areas, Tree of Life rugs are produced as prayer rugs. In Islam, the Tree of Life remains an important metaphor for the pathway between Heaven, Earth, and the underworld of Hell. #contemporaryart#reyzorro#whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #damienhirst #NewMediaArt#artbasel

name: 2019-09-19 06.14.05 2135917632841533848_tatemodern.jpg
text: yellow, is it me you’re looking for?—————————“I was talking about time. It's so hard for me to believe in it. Some things go. Pass on. Some things just stay. I used to think it was my rememory. You know. Some things you forget. Other things you never do. But it's not. Places, places are still there. If a house burns down, it's gone, but the place—the picture of it—stays, and not just in my rememory, but out there, in the world. What I remember is a picture floating around out there outside my head. I mean, even if I don't think it, even if I die, the picture of what I did, or knew, or saw is still out there. Right in the place where it happened.” — Toni Morrison, Beloved.—————————life as a gemini double capricorn is the eternal internal struggle of choosing between the absurdist punny caption and the cleverly selected prose. so today i just said f*** it and posted them both. who says you can’t be punny and pretentiously artsy all at once? not me! cause if you can’t do what you want on your own instagram posts, why even have an account, right? laugh unbridledly in your photos, post them with your artsier posed shots. candid moment shots like this really help me tap into the emotions i felt in that exact fraction of time when the image was shot. i remember seeing @momochavezz and @anaisengelmann behind @jesyelyse making me laugh and being supportive from the other side (swipe to the last image to see how we shot these at the #olafureliasson exhibit at the @tate modern). i remember what a fun day it was, how hot it was outside. the contentious uber ride from richmond, the hot stuffy tube ride to oxford circus, momo ordering a steak at sketch and only 3 tiny pieces coming out 😂 such a great day. and it’s funny, because the candid photos activate my memory senses much more vivid than the others. it really makes me think deeply about the power of visual storytelling, but also of capturing the unscripted, involuntary, fleeting moments of life. those are the moments we’re trying to relive when we record, the fraction of a second that you don’t want to end, that you wish you could live in forever. that’s the type of art that moves me most, and art i want to create.

name: 2019-09-19 14.53.23 2136179008168129519_tatemodern.jpg
text: Self-Portrait as a Lute Player (c.1615 - 17).🎨 Painted by Artemisia Gentileschi.Born: 8 July 1593, Rome, Italy.Died: 1653, Naples, Italy..🖼 Oil on canvas 77,5 × 71,8 cm..🏛 Location: Wadsworth Atheneum Museum of Art..📝 Her father was the Tuscan master Orazio Gentileschi. She and her brothers received their first artistic lessons in their father's workshop. It soon became clear that Artemisia was much more talented than her brothers.She made her first well-known work at the age of 17: Susanna and the Elders. Some think that Artemisia had been harrassed just like Susanna, and that she used that experience in the painting.Being a girl she was not accepted into any painting academy. Her father then had a colleague give her further lessons. This Agostino Tassi not only taught her painting but raped her as well. When that became public Tassi was sent to jail for a year.Artemisia's father quickly arranged a marriage, in order to save his daughter's honour. She married Pierantonio Stiattesi. The couple moved to Florence, where Gentileschi became a celebrated artist. She was accepted into a painters' academy, befriended Galileo Galilei and was protected by the powerful de' Medici family.In 1621 Artemisia Gentileschi moved back to Rome. She probably also spent some time in Venice between 1627 and 1630. This was not a very successful decade.Just like Caravaggio, who still had much influence at the time, Gentileschi moved to Naples, in 1630. She also worked in England for a while, beginning in 1638. Her father had a position at the court of Charles I. Some time after his death in 1639 she returned to Naples, where she was to work for the remainder of her life.It is not known exactly when she died. It is thought that she was one of many victims of the great pestilence that struck Naples in 1656.Her father was heavily influenced by the baroque master Caravaggio, and so was the young Artemisia. She is considered to be one of his most talented followers. Later she added classical influences into her work..(Fig 2, 3, 4: Details)...

name: 2019-09-19 16.29.37 2136227444076517241_tatemodern.jpg
text: We took the tin off a shed and twisted it a bit.We shaped an image and stuck it the ground.The sun rose this morning and the tide ran away.It is beautiful It is melodic the suns rays treading water as it runs away .When the water is gone the sun still dances ,so I’ve noticed.A complex symphony made to look so simple.A tidal flow of come and go. I can’t stop watching this.I don’t want to stop observing the stories around.I like writing things down.Of course I may exaggerate add and subtract a few words.I like words sometimes love them take them for granted.Pronunciation can be a hoot.Really sometimes I haven’t a clue what I’m trying to say.It seems someone always listens.Im so fucking glad we’ve come here today. #thoughtsculpture #monamuseum #queenslandartist #queenslandart #melbourneart #melbourneartists #byronbay #mullumbimby #brunswickheads #ballarat #bendigo #mona#tatemodern

(‘Colours’ series, 2018)‘COLOURS’ series is a comment on NUANCES of the language, AS WELL AS the nuance of ‘colours’...language can be equally USEFUL=USELESS...and I still, (steal) find it FUNDAMENTAL even if we all borrow the words we speak. ‘COLOURS’ is one of my comments on ‘THE ABSOLUTE POSSIBILITY OF DIS UNDERSTANDING’ which is not about ‘Misunderstanding’ it is about being understood in ways we do not really mean or maybe we do mean, ITS ABOUT THE CHANCE OF PLAYING finite and infinite GAMES. @artspace Reyzorro#contemporaryart#reyzorro @artspace #whitecubegallery #artnyc #moma#whitecube #whitechapelgallery #gagosian#themet #liquidskydsign#saatchigallery #miamibasel#serpentineuk #tatemodernmuseum #tatemodern #tatemodernlondon#haywardgallery #barbicancentre#pacegallery #artsy #londonartwalk #thefallmag#artmazemag#biennial#museumofmodernart #tatebritainmuseum #NewMediaArt #fashion #art#tategallery

text: Serene and beautiful this art is not!.Reveling in the depraved, the carnal and the misogynistic, the art of the Weimar Republic is often ugly and perhaps over-rated. But collectively, this is art that provides a thought-provoking record of a troubled and contradictory period.If you’re interested in reading more, my article ‘Magic Realism: The Art of Weimar Germany’ can be found by clicking the link in the bio (July 2019).Sergius Pauser (1896 – 1970) Self – Portrait with Mask (1926) The George Economou Collection © Angela Pauser and Wolfgang Pauser from Magic Realism: The Art of Weimar Germany at Tate Modern, London 30th July 2018 to 14th July 2019.#magicrealism #weimargermany #georgegrosz #albertbirkle #jeannemammen #sergiuspauser  #tate #tatemodern #figurativepainting #modernart #talkingaboutart #painter #painting #art

name: 2019-09-19 21.29.01 2136378133615476275_tatemodern.jpg
text: "МАСТЕР-КЛАСС В МОСКВЕ"⠀Когда:28 и 29 сентябряВремя: 13:00 — 19:00 с небольшим кофе-брейкомГде: в стадии выясненияСтоимость:4500р при оплате до 24 сентября5500р после 24-го сентябряв день мероприятия 6000р.(Предварительная оплата 50%)⠀"Маска – неотъемлемая составная карнавала. Гротеск. Бурлеск. Странное. Ужасное. Смешное. То, что способно удивлять и пробивать ту непроницаемую оболочку, в которую упаковало себя большинство современных людей. Маски не стесняются. Она (маска) не человек. Она притягивает и отталкивает, то есть разбалтывает стабильную уравновешенность стереотипа. Но в маске нужно уметь играть."Самая символически наполненная часть. Поэтому, с самым немногословным описанием программы.⠀Теория:- Мировая культура маски⠀Практика:- Основные приемы оживления маски. Принципы создания персонажа. Маска и взаимодействие с публикой.⠀Бонус- Основы безопасности движения в контексте спонтанной нагрузки, восстановления после травм или длительной профессиональной деформации.⠀Ведущие:Олег Скотников - основатель театра, актёр, режиссёр, директор.Анна Шишкина - основатель театра, художественный руководитель театра.⠀Регистрация в шапке профиля.

name: 2019-09-19 22.10.54 2136399215360740887_tatemodern.jpg
text: From today until 13 October, catch performances of Allora & Calzadilla’s 'Balance of Power' (2007) at Tate Modern. The work is a form of ‘living sculpture’ that involves three yoga practitioners wearing military uniforms and executing a sequence of yoga ‘warrior poses’. Addressing the meditative, spiritual and personal discipline of yoga and the collective body of the military under the authority of the state, 'Balance of Power' questions the distance between these military and non-military worlds, and explores the possible meanings and roots of ‘warrior’ poses within the culture of yoga.Performances take place between 1pm and 5pm on Thursdays and Sundays, and 4pm and 8pm on Fridays and Saturdays.Find out more at our website.Image: Allora & Calzadilla, 'Balance of Power' performed at 'Perplexed in Public' (group exhibition), Lisson Gallery, 13 June - 20 July 2008@tate #AlloraandCalzadilla #TateModern #LissonGallery

name: 2019-09-19 22.40.03 2136413889378836078_tatemodern.jpg
text: RIP MASSOUD ARABSHAHI..Arabshahi held his first solo exhibition at the Iran-India Centre, Tehran, in 1964, four years before graduating from the College of Decorative Arts, Tehran. His work includes oils on canvas, sculptures and architectural reliefs- among the latter commissions for the Office for Industry and Mining, Tehran, 1971, and the California Insurance Building, Santa Rosa, California, USA, 1985.His sources of inspiration comprise Achaemenid and Assyrian art as well as Babylonian carvings and inscriptions. Combining tradition and modernity. His work has been shown in a number of solo and group exhibitions in Iran, Europe and the United States including Two Modernist Iranian Pioneers, at the Tehran Museum of Contemporary Art, 2001; and Iranian Contemporary Art, Barbican Centre, London, 2001. He lives and works in Tehran and California.  #artist #art #culture #iran #contemporaryart #art #iranianartist #irancontemporary #artgallery #artwork #painting #dubai #exhibition #marbella #resort #gallery #middeleast #paris #tatemodern #saatchigallery #museum #moca #tmoca #britishmuseum #tatemodern #sothebyscontemporary #cheisties

name: 2019-09-19 22.53.35 2136420697512166933_tatemodern.jpg
text: Сегодня побывала в «нереальной реальности» или «реальной нереальности» ))) 🙄. Эту выставку нельзя пропустить! 😁👍🏻 Олафур Элиассон, современный датско-исландский художник, входит в десятку самых влиятельных художников в мире, представляет свои работы, объединяющие искусство, науку и природные явления. Борясь с пассивным характером традиционного восприятия искусства, он побуждает зрителя к активному участию. 39 метров шла через сильнейший цветной туман, как на другой планете побывала🚀.Зашла в калейдоскоп 🍭.Наблюдала в полной темноте за фонтаном, превращающим  воду каждый раз в новые фигуры. Поля из мха в помещении, целые поля )))😂Вот, что значит искусство будущего, а не всякие «картинки фигинки»😆🤓👌🏼. #tatemodern #london🇬🇧 #art #contemporaryart #arthunter

text: This riso zine was written and designed by @doingmedoingyou as part of her exhibition at the @wearethewomb symposium on International Women’s Day 2018. With Contrary to What is Agreeable, Emma studied the current position of diversity in the creative industries. The interactive poster exhibition used the meanings of various signs and symbols as a talking point for the importance of representation and she asked participants to visualise diversity through abstract shapes. Printed by @houseworkpress

text: P1❤️ #britishmuseumlondon P2🧡 #tatemodern P3💛 #vaxhall P4💚 #kensingtonhighstreet P5💙 #royalalberthall P6💜 #home P7🖤 #bricklane P8💖 #godsownjunkyard P9💝 #richmondpark 这些回忆都不会消失的它们都已经住在我的身体里陪我走过接下来的每一段路我会不断收获更多更多的美好回忆但是也永远不会忘记我所拥有过的这一切我在不断的告别告别我爱的人 也告别爱我的人These sweet memories happened in here will not disappear🧡They are already living in my bodyWalk with me through every step of the way❤️I will continue to have so many good memories…But I will never forget the time I lived in here.💙I am so tired of saying goodbye...Say goodbye to the person I love, and say goodbye to those who love me.In the end, I just wanna say I love London💌I am pretty sure I will see you again in my future:) Wish I won’t keep you waiting too long.❣️

text: Black Panel Dials, TakisWall relief from salvaged aeroplane gauges and instrument panels, sourced from military surplus stores. Panels that would show pilots elements affecting flights such as wind speed, are appropriated to create visual music. This was a call to scientists and activists to disrupt mass media and ruling governments technologies by developing ‘anti-tech’#art #sculpture #technology #antitech #tatemodern

name: 2019-09-20 04.40.05 2136595094963224234_tatemodern.jpg
text: I haven’t posted in a while. I’ve been busy trying to figure out what direction I want my art to go in. With limited finances I find it a real challenge to sometimes do everything that I’d like to do in order to help me move forward. I always seem to shy away from taking risks and don’t really invest anything into what I’m trying to achieve.However I made a very important decision today that I truly believe will help me get to where I want to be.I took a deep breathe and signed up to take part in @alimapletoft 6 week Designer Foundation Course to help me learn, grow and most important of all be inspired. ....................The art featured is framed but still a work in progress...like me.

name: 2019-09-20 04.46.32 2136598349088641545_tatemodern.jpg
text: Picasso’s ‘Motherhood’ of 1901. Picasso at this time was profoundly moved by a visit to the Saint Lazare prison in Paris for prostitutes where there were also children accommodated.  It sparked off extraordinarily powerful, expressionistic images - in this example one that is overtly religious. The landscape is not so far from the Norwegian Munch - a patchwork landscape using the complementary colours of green and red provides a striking framework for the pathos of the figures. The painting also underlines the current tension between the National Gallery led by its Spanish director Gabriele Finaldi and the Tate Modern. It had been agreed before that the ‘cut-off’ date for the National Gallery would be 1900. However as Finaldi objects this is pretty ridiculous. For instance, how can you explain Cubism without reference to Cezanne’s works before 1900? Note the date of this ‘recent’ aquisition = 1901! #Nationalgallery #tatemodern #picasso #art #design # religion #madonnaandchild #London #museums #spain #paris #france #expressionism #tourism #culture #finearts #religiousimages #catholicism #cezanne #norway

text: В V&A открывается новая, по-настоящему сказочная выставка 🦄!⠀Не успела еще отгреметь выставка Dior, как музей V&A готов представить еще одну невероятную экспозицию. 🏛 На этот раз здесь покажут работы известного современного фотографа Тима Уолкера. Выставка под названием “Wonderful things” открывает сказочный мир чудес, который оживает в голове автора 🎨. Каждый зал — настоящее приключение. Гигантские изумрудные драконы 🐉 и длинноногие розовые гепарды под потолком, комнаты-шкатулки в стиле китайских ларчиков, традиционные английские чайные комнаты ☕️ с камином — все это лишь часть большого представления.⠀Ни за что не пропусти это замечательное мероприятие!⠀😱 Что? Tim Walker: Wonderful ThingsГде? text: Portrait with monkey - Frida Kahlo, 1938. It is in her iconic self portraits, unrivalled in their poignant beauty, that Kahlo depicts both her isolation and also her indomitable spirit and sense of self. The exhibition also reveals the less well-known aspects of her work; her powerful political insights about national identity, the plight of the poor, the march of technology and Mexico's relationship with its neighbour the USA. #tate #tatemodern #fridakahlo #fridakahloart #art #usa #americanart #moma #beautiful

name: 2019-09-20 14.05.14 2136879546586446558_tatemodern.jpg
text: The Ship of Tolerance Thames River LondonImage copyright @totallythames festivalART FOR CHANGEThe ship is an international art project created by Ilya and Emilia Kabakov, two of the most celebrated artists of their generation and widely known for their large-scale installations. A retrospective of their work was held at Tate Modern in 2018.The Ship of Tolerance – a 60-foot long, hand-crafted wooden ship - is dedicated to educating and inspiring young people through the universal language of art. Its unique potency emerges via a curated workshop programme with primary schools, refugee groups and cultural organisations in which children paint silk panels to make sails for The Ship of Tolerance based on their discussion of diversity and the agency ideas gain through art.First launched in Egypt in 2005, The Ship of Tolerance has subsequently been created in various locations around the world including Venice, Havana, Moscow, New York and Rome. The project was awarded the prestigious Cartier Prize for the Best Art Project of the Year in 2010.For its presentation in London, the sails of The Ship of Tolerance have been made by children from forty London primary schools, from Great Ormond Street Hospital and from refugee centres in Birmingham, Leeds, Peterborough and Calais.Produced by The Kabakov Foundation and Art Action Change in collaboration with Thames Festival Trust. Supported by Bloomberg Philanthropies, Royal Docks, VolkerBrooks Ltd, NDL Foundation, Sofia Barattieri Weinstein and Frieze London. Supporting the UN Global Goals.#ship #art #publicart #thames #london #tatemodern #festival #tolerance #acceptance #peace

text: 04. 21:47 Jaden Raxel - Mystical (Original Mix) [Somatic Records]..Pictured: proto-painting..⁣⁣⁣Die Zukunst ist hier [The future is here⁣⁣⁣]..Dialogue with The Bottle Rack (also called Bottle Dryer or Hedgehog) (Egouttoir or Porte-bouteilles or Hérisson) is a proto-Dada artwork created in 1914 by Marcel Duchamp...Artistic practice:⁣⁣⁣.⁣⁣⁣.The term refers to the ways in which an artist goes about his/her work. Artistic practice goes beyond the physical activities of making artistic products and can include influences, ideas, materials as well as tools and skills...The natural duality and technological explanations, drawing simple shapes and forms in various programming languages, re-visualizing Giotto’s 14th-century Assisi fresco “Exorcism of the Demons at Arezzo,” digitally mediated name: 2019-09-20 16.04.14 2136939438209507674_tatemodern.jpg
text: Winter Landscape (c.1881).🎨 Painted by Ivan Aivazovsky.Born: 29 July 1817, Feodosia, Crimea, Ukraine.Died: 2 May 1900, Feodosia, Crimea, Ukraine..🖼 Oil on canvas 33 x 43 cm..⭐️ Famous Armenian painter who knew the sea and loved it sincerely..📝 Drawing ability of young Aivazovsky attracted the attention of A. Kaznacheyev, the town-governor, who helped Aivazovsky to enter the high school at Simferopol and in 1833, the St Petersburg Academy of Arts.At the age of twenty he graduated from the Art Academy of St. Petersburg with a gold medal. At the age of 25 he have already gained international fame.During the period of 1840-1844 Aivazovsky, as a pensioner of the Academy of Arts, spent time in Italy, traveled to Germany, France, Spain, and Holland. He worked much and had many exhibitions, meeting everywhere with success. He painted a lot of marine landscapes, which became very popular in Italy.Aivazovsky's name is intricately bound with the sea. "Perhaps no one in Europe has painted the extraordinary beauty of the sea with so much feeling and expressiveness as Aivazovsky has", writes V. Adasov.When in 1844 the artist returned to St. Petersburg, he was awarded the title of Academician, and became attached to the General Naval Headquarters. This allowed him to travel much with Russian fleet expeditions on different missions; he visited Turkey, Greece, Egypt, America. From 1846 to 1848 he painted several canvases with naval warfare as the subject; the pictures portrayed historical battles of the Russian Fleet.Neither financial security nor life in Palace interested him. He returned to his native land, built a workplace/home on the seashore and, until the last days of his life, dedicates himself to the work that he loved.Aivazovsky left more than 6000 pictures. Most of his works are world-famous..(Fig 2, 3, 4: Details)...

text: The Bankside Coal Power Station aka #tatemodern. Olafur, Nan, Kara, WeiWei, all the contemporary art heavy hitters...but the star is the #infrastructure. I love seeing solar arrays gleaming next to the coal smoke stack. Mums with strollers in turbine rooms. Selfies in fly ash tanks. The transformers outside still power this side of River Thames, with the waste heat  used for climate control for all the art. Beyond modern, this is a glimpse into our cleaner renewable future. #ilovelondon🇬🇧
